<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-17 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Asks Desney Not to Bow to Arab Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak has asked the Walt Desney World not to yield to Arab
pressure regarding Israel's participation in Desney's millennium
celebrations at Epcot Park in Florida.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Friday, Barak blasted the Arabs for their
efforts to stop an Israeli pavilion from opening at the park.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Israel has planned to stage an exhibit
emphasizing Jerusalem inside its pavilion.
</P>
<P>
The Arab delegations to the celebrations strongly oppose the
exhibit, arguing that it bears political impact by designating
Jerusalem as Israel's capital.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Arab delegations, which included ambassadors
from Morocco and the United Arab Emirates, presented on Wednesday
Walt Desney World's President Al Weiss with a memo outlining their
objections to the exhibit. They also asked Desney to remove the
exhibit from the pavilion, otherwise, the Arab nations would
boycott the celebration.
</P>
<P>
Weiss planned to talk to Arab leaders again on Friday to
head off the controversy over Israel's exhibit.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts to harm Israel's standing on Jerusalem as its capital
failed in the past and would fail in the future," Barak said in
his statement, adding that Israel does not expect Desney to yield
to such pressures.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry sent a letter to Disney Chairman
Michael Eisner Wednesday, which expressed Israel's confidence
that the exhibit will be presented in its entirety.
</P>
<P>
With the participation of about 35 countries, the 15-month
Desney celebrations are scheduled to open on October 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
