<HEADLINE> Jobs, Crime, Italians' Prime Concerns, Surveys Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A scarcity of jobs and a rise in
crime proved to be by far the most pressing of Italians' worries
in the latest six-monthly survey of national thinking carried out
by the Italian National Council for the Economy and Employment
(CNEL).
</P>
<P>
Of those polled, 48 percent said creating jobs was the prime
concern though over 50 percent of those interviewed in some
southern areas cited joblessness as the nation's biggest problem.
</P>
<P>
The number of those prepared to approach the problem by making
the labor market more flexible rather than via state intervention
rose by 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Those ready to back flexible, lower-paid and less guaranteed
contracts rose to 45 percent, compared to 39 percent against.
</P>
<P>
A close second in the national rankings of bugbears was crime,
with 20 percent of the 4,500 interviewed putting it in top slot, a
rise of 3 percent on the previous survey.
</P>
<P>
In the field of politics, the number of those polled in favor
of neo-liberal free-market solutions was up 3-5 percent in the
last two years, to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Those holding to what the survey called "conservative"
positions was steady at around 53 percent.
</P>
<P>
On ways to fight crime, the CNEL found that the Italians are
about evenly divided between those asking for stiffer sentences,
47 percent, and others who say that trials must be swift and
efficient. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
