<HEADLINE> GA President Urges Equitable Representation, Gender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The principle of
equitable geographical representation and gender balance must be
respected, particularly in the appointment of staff to senior
level positions, President of the General Assembly Theo-Ben
Gurirab stressed here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion of the United Nations Staff Day,
September 17, Gurirab said U.N. staff represents a microcosm of
the peoples of the world and more senior staff from developing
countries should be appointed to these senior positions.
</P>
<P>
On the challenges facing the United Nations, Gurirab said they
include but are not limited to issues as important as career
development, staff mobility, the safety and security of
humanitarian staff and protection of United Nations personnel as
well as human resources management in general.
</P>
<P>
On the threshold of the next century, the United Nations is
faced with momentous tasks, including issues such as its reform,
globalization, gender equality, sustainable development and
protection of the environment, regional conflict and the resulting
refugee crises, HIV-AIDS pandemic and the plight of children, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing these issues requires foresight and dedication on
the part of Member States, and it also requires a cadre of
motivated staff, responding to the Charter requirements of
efficiency, competence and integrity, Gurirab said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
