<HEADLINE> UK Gov't Admits Acting Illegally on GM Crop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Britain's green campaigners
scored a victory over genetically-modified (GM) crops Friday when
the British government admitted that it acted illegally in
allowing trials of GM crops to go ahead.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in August, Friends of the Earth (FoE) presented papers
to the High Court in London, calling for a judicial review of the
British government's licensing of crop trials.
</P>
<P>
The environmental pressure group claimed that the government
was wrong to allow agrochemical firm AgrEvo UK to switch one of
its tests of GM rapeseed from spring to autumn planting without
submitting a new application to an advisory committee monitoring
the crops.
</P>
<P>
Speaking Friday at a news conference, Michael Meacher,
Britain's environment minister, said the government has decided
not to contest FoE's challenge to the legality of the tests.
</P>
<P>
"Following legal advice, the government has decided not to
contest the judicial review of proceedings instigated by Friends
of the Earth in respect of licensing of certain GM trials," said
Meacher.
</P>
<P>
"We are accepting that on this point we acted illegally," he
said, adding that the decision not to contest the judicial review
won by FoE was made on technical grounds and was not based on
fears over the crop's safety.
</P>
<P>
Meacher said that the British government's program of
farm-scale GM crop trials will continue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
