<HEADLINE> U.N. Condemns Fatal Attack Against Aid Worker in Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The death of an aid
worker from the U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF), who was fatally
wounded in an ambush Wednesday during a campaign to vaccinate
children against polio, drew strong reactions from the UNICEF and
a top U.N. official for humanitarian affairs.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Thursday in New York, the UNICEF lamented
with profound regret and sorrow in the passing away of Ayub Sheikh
Yerow who died Thursday morning from a gun shot wound in a North
Mogadishu hospital.
</P>
<P>
Ayub was wounded on the evening of September 15 while traveling
by road on a planning assignment for the October National
Immunization Day to vaccinate approximately 1 million children in
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
"Dr. Ayub's death adds one more to a growing list of casualties
involving humanitarian workers courageously seeking to carry out
life-saving missions in extremely dangerous situations," the
UNICEF said, stressing that such attacks were a completely
unacceptable violation of international law and fundamental human
rights.
</P>
<P>
Echoing this statement, U.N. Under-Secretary-General for
Humanitarian Affairs Sergio Vieira de Mello said in a statement
that the attack served as "a grim reminder" of the impunity with
which lives are taken in conflict areas around the world.
</P>
<P>
"I trust that local authorities will take immediate measures
to apprehend those responsible and ensure that the safety of
humanitarian workers is guaranteed," de Mello said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
