<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Premature Baby Saved in UK Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Surgeons have made British
medical history by operating on a baby while he was still in his
mother's womb, BBC reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Baby Jaydon, now 13 days old, was the first premature baby in
Britain to receive a life-saving windpipe operation while he was
still halfway inside his mother's womb.
</P>
<P>
The operation, which took place at Newcastle-upon-Tyne's Royal
Victoria Infirmary in September, involved keeping the baby in
suspended labor while doctors unblocked his windpipe.
</P>
<P>
The baby's mother, Joanne Vasey, aged 17, went into labor when
she was only 32 weeks pregnant. Pre-natal scans suggested a
windpipe blockage, which meant the baby would suffocate as soon as
his umbilical cord was cut.
</P>
<P>
The only solution was to open the mother's abdomen and keep him
in pre-birth limbo so that he can still receive oxygen through the
umbilical cord.
</P>
<P>
A 20-strong medical team battled to correct the problem and the
45-minute operation was a success.
</P>
<P>
Similar operations have been carried out in the United States
before, but this is the first time it has been performed in
Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
