<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Arabia and the Philippines have signed a
preliminary agreement on mutual investment guarantees.
</P>
<P>
A final agreement in this respect will be signed next year, the
Arabic daily Al Hayat reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine ambassador in Riyadh has said that the agreement
will broaden trade and economic relations between the two
countries. It will also encourage the private sector in both
states to explore commercial and investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi and Philippine sides had agreed at their first
meeting of the joint committee, held in Manila last April, to
conclude an investment guarantee accord with the objective to
promote trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian Arab Bank has led other banks in 1998
in terms of financial performance, according to a study undertaken
by Jordanian banker Mofleh Aql.
</P>
<P>
The Arab Bank ranked first with regard to the volume of assets
and deposits, net profits before taxation, interest rate on the
paid capital before taxation, the interest rate on assets before
taxation, and the profits distributed among shareholders, the
Arabic newspaper Al Hayat said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The study points out that assets of the Jordanian Arab Bank in
1998 amounted to about 2.9 billion dinars (4.1 billion U.S.
dollars), the equivalent of 31.7 percent of the total assets of
Jordan's banks.
</P>
<P>
The study also said that the Arab Bank has 2.67 billion dinars
(3.81 billion dollars) in deposits, representing 33.6 percent of
the total deposits in Jordanian banks.
</P>
<P>
JEDDAH -- Over 100 health-related companies and organizations
will take part in the Saudi Health Care Exhibition '99 that is to
open Monday in the Saudi port city of Jeddah.
</P>
<P>
The fair, organized by "Harthy Fairs Ltd" under the auspices of
the Saudi Ministry of Health, attracts local companies as well
firms from the U.S., Britain, India, Iran, Lebanon, Australia,
Sweden and France.
</P>
<P>
Various seminars, among other events, will be held on the
sidelines of the fair, which include those on cooperative medical
insurance in Saudi Arabia, the importance of correct data of
health care services and on technology in medical diagnosis hosted
by Saudi-German hospitals.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's net public debt rose by 281 million
U.S. dollars to 18.46 billion dollars at the end of July compared
with the previous month, the central bank said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in its monthly bulletin that domestic debt
increased to 13.67 billion dollars compared with 13.44 billion
dollars in June.
</P>
<P>
Foreign debt rose to 4.772 billion dollars at the end of July
compared to 4.716 billion dollars a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's gross foreign reserves rose by 176 million
U.S. dollars in mid-September to 6.689 billion dollars from 6.513
billion dollars at the end of August, the central bank said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Gross foreign reserves, which include deposits by commercial
banks and government agencies, stood at 6.445 billion dollars in
mid-August.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign reserves were 6.41 billion dollars at the
end of 1998 and 5.93 billion dollars at the end of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
