<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Researcher Creates Novel Data Storage Technique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A British professor has
developed a new data storage technology which promises to enable
palmtop PCs to carry as much data as a mainframe computer.
</P>
<P>
The technique is so efficient that "2,300 gigabytes of data can
be squeezed on to a device the size of a credit card," Financial
Times said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The technology, created by Ted Williams, emeritus professor of
electronic engineering in Britain's Keele University, relies on a
new family of metal alloys which allow huge amounts of information
to be stored inside the material.
</P>
<P>
It then operates in conjunction with a new optical method of
accessing the information on multiple levels inside the material
using sophisticated software.
</P>
<P>
The system, which has no moving parts, is said to be far more
reliable than existing PC hard disks. As it uses much current
hardware technology, the devices can also be quickly put into
production after a short development period.
</P>
<P>
"The technology is scaleable, either up or down, so that even
wristwatches will be capable of handling a memory capacity of more
than 100 gigabytes," professor Ted Williams was quoted as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
