<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Defense Minister Visits Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Defense Minister
Socrates Hasikos left here Friday for an official visit to Greece
for talks with his Greek counterpart Akis Tsohatzopoulos.
</P>
<P>
Hasikos said before departure that the two sides will discuss
bilateral cooperation in defense and will review a joint defense
pact signed in November 1993.
</P>
<P>
Under the pact, Greece will provide air, sea and land coverage
to Cyprus in case of a new Turkish offensive against the island.
</P>
<P>
The minister also announced that Cyprus' annual National Guard
exercise codenamed "Nikiforos" has been brought forward to
October 2 to 7.
</P>
<P>
He said that the military manoeuvre "will take place as it is
the only exercise our small army carries out."
</P>
<P>
Explaining why the exercise has been brought forward, he said
"President Clerides is now in New York for important meetings and
the government decided it would be better it took place before any
talks."
</P>
<P>
Clerides has been in the U.S. since Thursday to address the
U.N. General Assembly and he will hold talks with
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and other key players in efforts
to settle the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
A new effort is now underway for peace talks to be resumed at
the end of October and Annan is expected to extend invitations to
the Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot sides to attend the talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations have not been held for the past two years, due to
preconditions set by the Turkish side for recognition of the
breakaway state in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish side also demands establishment of a confederation
of two states on the island. 
</P>
