<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: What Causes Economic Crisis in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Scarcity of foreign currencies
and the fluctuation of exchange rate manipulated by speculators
are listed by the Angolan government as the main causes of the
current economic crisis distorting the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos presided over an
emergent meeting of the Council of Ministers in Luanda Thursday,
at which ministers and experts also attributed the economic crisis
to the reduction of goods supply, the augmentation of public
expenditure and the existence of a large amount of counterfeit
notes.
</P>
<P>
It is true that the country has no enough foreign currencies to
fill the bottomless abyss in the exchange market, for Angola is a
country that is making a living on the mono-economy, namely on
petroleum export.
</P>
<P>
The long-term depression of the price of petroleum in the world
market since 1997 has distorted the southern African country. The
lowest price under 10 U.S. dollars per barrel early this year gave
a decisive punch to the country, which was forced to abandon its
fixed rate of exchange on July 3.
</P>
<P>
In consequence of the low petroleum price and the so-called
manipulation of the exchange market, the national currency
readjusted kwanza saw a sharp decline in its value.
</P>
<P>
At this moment, the exchange rate in readjusted kwanza against
U.S. dollar has reached seven million readjusted kwanza for one
dollar, devaluating by 900 percent in three months. On July 2,
readjusted kwanza was officially priced at 700,000 for one dollar.
</P>
<P>
It is also recognized by analysts here that the reduction of
goods supply and the existence of counterfeit notes also perturbed
the economic order. But all the reasons aforementioned are not
the fundamental cause of the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, what is the fundamental cause of the economic crisis?
Local analysts pointed out that it is the civil war.
</P>
<P>
Angola is the second largest oil-producing country in
sub-Saharan Africa, and is abundant in diamond resource. For a
country with only ten million population, the rich mineral
resources mean great potential in economic development. But the
war impeded it from going ahead.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year-old civil war has destroyed most of the
infrastructures around the country, created over two million
displaced people in need for food, potable water and other
necessities, and mined a lot of the principal roads and then
prevented the government from exploring for more mineral
resources.
</P>
<P>
The impact of war on agriculture is most terrible. Due to the
rampant war all around the country, most farmers and peasants were
forced to leave their villages for cities and towns, where the
cultivated land is rare.
</P>
<P>
Since some local governments organized self-sufficient
agricultural production, the displaced people can not get the
necessary means of production such as tools and seeds.
</P>
<P>
Also due to the ambushes frequently launched by the rebel
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA),
transportation columns encountered a lot of difficulties on their
way to the interior parts of the country as they have to cross the
rural areas controlled by the UNITA rebels led by Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
UNITA has recently changed their tactics. They drove many
rural residents into the cities and besieged them, in a bid to
force the government to pay more attention to helping the
displaced people and to scatter the strength of the government
troops.
</P>
<P>
It is very difficult for the government troops to find their
enemies, for the UNITA rebels have scattered into small groups and
hid in forests and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
But the attack on civil vehicles and small villages are
worrying the government.
</P>
<P>
So, what the displaced people can do is to wait. They have
little food, water and seeds. To them, money means nothing because
there are few goods supply due to the difficult transportation.
</P>
<P>
In big cities such as the national capital city of Luanda,
people are also living a miserable life, with the fast rising
prices of the daily necessities.
</P>
<P>
Because the country imports most of food and other necessities,
the Angolan people are suffering from the fluctuating exchange
rate of the readjusted kwanza against the U.S. dollar. But during
the period of war, production of food and those necessities is
impossible.
</P>
<P>
That is the dilemma all Angolans are facing. Most people have
expressed their eagerness for the end of war as soon as possible,
which will lighten their way to the happy life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
