<HEADLINE> Foreign Direct Investment in Tanzania to Surpass </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct
investment (FDI) in Tanzania this year is projected to reach 231.4
million U.S. dollars, compared with 181.5 million during the
1997/98 fiscal year, Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a speech with a copy available here, Mkapa told the National
Press Club in Washington D.C., USA, that with the improvement of
investment environment in his country, foreign direct investments
kept pouring in.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian president, who is on a working visit to the
United States, attributed the increasing FDI to political
stability, correct economic and fiscal policies in the east
African country.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Mkapa said Tanzania has investment incentives that
offer a well-balanced package, especially in mining. Transfer of
capital and profits is allowed and currency is freely convertible
in Tanzania, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said investments in Tanzania are protected against
 arbitrary nationalization and expropriation, and the Tanzania
Investment Center is being strengthened to be a truly one-stop
center that will assist investors in all issues.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian president also said that there are no
restrictions in enterprise entering into technology transfer
agreements, and any foreign business operating in Tanzania may
obtain credit for domestic financial institutions up to set
limits.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said although Tanzania does not have facilities and
efficiency as good as the United States, the country is serious in
co-operating with foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
He asked U.S. investors, tourists and traders "to take a second
 objective look at Tanzania and the opportunities it offers."
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Tanzania was the sixth largest destination for inward
direct investment in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
In 1994/95, foreign direct investment in Tanzania was only
104.1 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
