<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Links High Blood Pressure to Osteoporosis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Researchers from Britain and
the United States said Friday they have found the first proof that
women with higher blood pressure are more likely to suffer from
osteoporosis later in life.
</P>
<P>
The scientists, from St George's Hospital in London, the London
School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, and the University of
Pittsburgh, established the link after studying more than 3,500
elderly women from four areas in the United States.
</P>
<P>
They measured bone density, rate of hip bone loss and blood
pressure in those post-menopausal women and the measurements were
repeated three and a half years later.
</P>
<P>
The study found that women with higher blood pressure had
greater and faster loss of bone minerals than those with lower
blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
Even when adjusted for factors which affect either osteoporosis
or high blood pressure, such as smoking, the researchers found
there was still a significantly greater bone loss among
hypertensive women.
</P>
<P>
Previous research showed hypertensive people excrete higher
amounts of calcium in their urine than those with low blood
pressure.
</P>
<P>
Writing in The Lancet medical journal, the researchers
suggested that calcium lost in the urine is replaced through
calcium stripped from the bone, causing bone weakening, which
could eventually result in osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
They suggested that changes to the diet, such as cutting salt
intake, could both reduce blood pressure and delay the onset of
osteoporosis in women.
</P>
<P>
"Decreased salt intake should therefore lessen the risk of
osteoporosis and hip fractures in elderly people and also have a
blood-pressure-lowering effect," they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
