<HEADLINE> Britain Rejects Fayed's Diana Murder Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The British Foreign Office on
Friday dismissed claims by Mohamed al-Fayed that the security
service had caused the death of Princess Diana and his son Dodi.
</P>
<P>
Henri Paul, the driver of the car in which the two died in
Paris two years ago, had acted by order of Britain's MI5 and MI6
security agencies and the French intelligence service, Harrods
store owner al-Fayed told BBC radio Friday.
</P>
<P>
"He drove into the tunnel under instructions of MI6 and MI5 and
French intelligence," al-Fayed said. "They killed him. They had to
kill him, of course."
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Office spokesman said the allegations were "baseless"
and "deeply upsetting to the Royal Family and the princess's
family."
</P>
<P>
Al-Fayed has persisted with his version of events despite a
French judicial inquiry that found Paul was drunk when his
Mercedes limousine crashed at high speed into a pillar in a Paris
road tunnel on August 31, 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
