<HEADLINE> Nomads Urged to Keep Order in N. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KAMPALA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Karimojong, a nomad
people in northeastern Uganda, have been urged to assist the
government to restore peace and sustain development in their
region.
</P>
<P>
This call was made by Uganda's State Minister in charge of
Northern Uganda Rehabilitation Omony Ojwok at the district or
Moroto in the region Friday, Radio Uganda reported in the evening
news.
</P>
<P>
He said that without the help from the local people, it would
be much more difficult for the government to restore peace in the
region characterized by cattle rustling.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said that as many as 500 Karimojong were killed
in the fierce battle between the Bokora and the Matheniko last
week. The government intervened by sending troops into the region
to restore peace.
</P>
<P>
A military gunship was reportedly used to disperse those
engaged in fighting between the two hostile groups. President
Yoweri Museveni has confirmed that the government troops have
killed some Karimojong warriors had been killed in the clashes.
But he declined to give the exact number.
</P>
<P>
The two groups often accuse each other of rustling cattle from
their respective camps and thus engage in fighting and counter
raid. Another report said that the Karimojong warriors have some
8,000 guns, a big threat to the regional peace.
</P>
<P>
There have been loud outcries from the Parliament demanding
disarming the warriors, but the government has not yet determined
to do so.
</P>
<P>
The Karamoja area has been neglected in terms of development
by all successive post-independence governments. It's semi-arid
and characterized by lack of water supply, draught, food shortage
and poor communications.
</P>
<P>
The people there are nomads moving around in search of pasture
and water for their cattle. Cattle rustling and insecurity have
been the common feature of Karamoja. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
