<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Minister Sets Out Timetable for Digital TV Turn-On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The switch from analogue to
digital TV in Britain could start as early as 2006 and be
completed by 2010, British Culture Secretary Chris Smith said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, speaking at the Royal Television Society conference in
Cambridge, England, he stressed that the introduction of the
"digital revolution" will depend on the progress made by British
broadcasters and manufactures, with viewers' interests coming
first.
</P>
<P>
Smith promised that the government will not switch off existing
television signals until at least 95 percent of viewers have
equipped themselves with digital sets or set-top boxes.
</P>
<P>
Before switch over, digital services will also have to be
available to 99.4 percent of the population, he said, adding that
the digital equipment must be affordable for a vast majority of
population, and including those on low and fixed income and older
people.
</P>
<P>
Smith also outlined his aim that following the switch over from
existing analogue to digital television, every home in the country
with a television and telephone would have access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to Britain's TV industry executives in which he
claimed it was an appropriate time to "think daring thoughts,"
Smith said, "I intend to provide you with as clear a timetable as
I can so that you can plan investment with confidence."
</P>
<P>
So far about 1.5 million households in Britain, representing
about 3 million adults, receive digital television through a
satellite dish, aerial or cable.
</P>
<P>
But analogue terrestrial signals are still the only source of
television for the 70 percent of British households who do not
subscribe to pay TV.
</P>
<P>
Commercial broadcasters have been urging Smith to name a date
to switch off traditional terrestrial signals, to encourage
consumers to buy new equipment and reduce uncertainty about their
multi-billion pound investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burns Overcomes Mud to Lead China Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUAIROU, Beijing, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Subaru star Briton
Richard Burns led at the end of the first leg of the China Rally
on a day of attrition that saw 26 of the 67 cars that started
failed to complete the first day.
</P>
<P>
Burns will take a 19.8 seconds lead over Frenchman Didier
Auriol, driving a Toyota, into the second leg, while reigning
world champion Tommi Makinen of Finland, on a Mitsubishi, was
poised to strike in third place just 2.6 seconds behind Auriol.
</P>
<P>
Burns' teammate Juha Kankkunen, also a Finn, was fourth from
Carlos Sainz of Spain in the second Toyota and Finn Harri
Rovanpera in the sole remaining SEAT.
</P>
<P>
Both Ford Focus dirvers, Colin McRae and Thomas Radstrom,
failed to complete even one stage before retiring and were joined
on the sidelines by Piero Liatti, also SEAT, and Freddy Loix of
Mitsubishi from the factory - backed teams.
</P>
<P>
Amazingly both Ford cars damaged their suspensions in exactly
the same way after both hit the same obstable on the third turn of
the first special stage.
</P>
<P>
"We ran over the concerete which we had noted in the recce,
without regarding it as a major hazard, but unfortunatedly it
damaged the suspension too badly to continue," McRae said.
</P>
<P>
"It's just a samll area of reliability that we need to look at,
" he added.
</P>
<P>
Makinen set the early pace and led clearly before he hit a tree
on a right hand bend damaging his rear suspension and side of the
car. He lost about 30 seconds and had to climb through the window
to get out of his car at the service park.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi team mechanics repaired the car that was again
running strongly at the finish of the day.
</P>
<P>
"I am a bit disappointed to have made this mistake, because it
was going so well and we were leading by over half a minute,"
Makinen said.
</P>
<P>
"There is a long way to go and I think we can keep our World
Championship lead."
</P>
<P>
Burns had set a consevative pace that paid off well for him
today.
</P>
<P>
"I very deliberately ran at the pace I thought was right for me,
the car, and the conditions," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are only a short way into an event that is new to most of
us, so tactically the next couple of days are very difficult to
call.'
</P>
<P>
Tomorrow is the longest and most grueling day of the event and
if the forecast showers arrive it will be difficult for all
drivers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
