<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Faces Critical Choices as Population Passes 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. report
highlights the critical challenges and choices facing countries as
the global population passes 6 billion -- twice what it was in
1960.
</P>
<P>
Nafis Sadik, executive director of the United Nations
Population Fund (UNFPA), will launch the report, entitled "State
of World Population 1999," in London at a press conference at the
Foreign Press Association, starting at 11:00 a.m. local time (1000
GMT), on September 22, the UNFPA said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Day of 6 Billion will be marked next month, October 12, and
more than 78 million people will be added this year. With more
than a billion young people entering their childbearing years,
population will continue to grow well into the 21st century,
specially in poor countries.
</P>
<P>
At a landmark 1994 conference in Cairo, 179 governments agreed
that population is closely linked to prospects for alleviating
poverty, empowering women and protecting the environment.
</P>
<P>
They acknowledged the right to reproductive health, and called
for gender quality and universal access to reproductive health
care including family planning.
</P>
<P>
The UNFPA helps developing countries to improve reproductive
health and family planning based on individual choice, and to
formulate population policies in support of sustainable
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
