<HEADLINE> Clinton Declares Hurricane Emergency in New Jersey State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton declared an emergency in New Jersey Friday because of
Hurricane Floyd, paving the way for the state to apply for federal
money to help with cleanup.
</P>
<P>
The White House said in a statement that Clinton's move means
the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) can coordinate all
disaster relief efforts in nine hard-hit New Jersey counties.
</P>
<P>
The federal government is expected to provide 75 percent of the
money needed for debris removal and other immediate needs in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Clinton declared a major disaster in North
Carolina, and released 528 million U.S. dollars to the FEMA to
help hurricane victims. 
</P>
