<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana's Economy to Be Boosted by Diamond Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Botswana's economy will
be boosted by diamond sales of a forecast 680 million to 700
million U.S. dollars in August, according to a report reaching
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The way it is going it appears that the government budget will
have a big windfall this year," Permanent Secretary in the
Botswanan Ministry of Minerals, Energy and Water Affairs, Blackie
Marole, was quoted as saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Our (annual budget) was based on estimates that we would sell
75 percent of our total (diamond) production, but now it looks
like will sell the entire production," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Fleming Martin and Investec Securities reportedly forecast a
largest seventh sight on record from this year's seventh diamond
sight organized by De Beers' Central Selling Organization
responsible for marketing diamonds produced in Botswana and South
Africa.  The previous largest was 550 million dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Investec predicted the August sight "could reach 700 million
dollars or above," and added that the De Beers' Central Selling
Organization was poised to sell more diamonds in 1999 than any
other year on record.
</P>
<P>
The Botswanan government in January forecast a budget deficit
of 400 million pula (80 million dollars) in the current fiscal
year ending on April 30 due to the expected poor performance of
the diamond industry.
</P>
<P>
The country's mining company, Debswana -- a joint venture
between South African diamond giant De Beers and the Botswana
government -- is the world' s largest diamond producer by value.
Last year alone, it produced more than 19,000 carats.
</P>
<P>
The sale of diamonds accounts for about 80 percent of
Botswana's export revenues and 33 percent of its GDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-17 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
