<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary 2000GMT, Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat met secretly Thursday night in Ramallah,
discussing negotiations for a permanent peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
David Ziso, Barak's spokesman, confirmed the holding of
the meeting, but declined to give details. Israel Radio said the
meeting last several hours. (BC-Israel-Talks)
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas has said that a
settlement to the 36-year-old Cyprus problem could come within
five months if the international community treats the two sides on
the island as equals.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the Turkish Daily News published
on Friday, Denktas said that as long as the Greek Cypriot side
continues to be accorded the title of the sole government of the
entire island, they will not feel the need to
compromise. (BC-Turkey-Cyprus)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has pledged that
Israel would ensure the well-being and safety of its local
militiamen in southern Lebanon in any peace settlement with
Lebanon and Syria, local media reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Gen. Antoine Lahad, commander of the
pro-Israel South Lebanon Army, Barak reiterated that he is making
every effort to reach a peace agreement that will allow for an
Israeli troop withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which took place Thursday in Tel Aviv, was Barak's
first meeting, as prime minister, with Lahad, the local daily
Jerusalem Post said. (BC-Israel-Lebanon)
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The United Nations Iraq-Kuwait Observer Mission
(UNIKOM) said on Friday it had sent a team to the border area to
investigate the killing of two Kuwaiti border guards.
</P>
<P>
"We sent the panel to the border region to investigate the
incident and a report will be referred to the U.N. headquarters in
New York which will decide whether to issue a public statement,"
UNIKOM spokesman Abdullahi Rijal told the Kuwait News Agency by
telephone. (BC-UNIKOM-Kuwait-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has asked the
Walt Desney World not to yield to Arab pressure regarding
Israel's participation in Desney's millennium celebrations at
Epcot Park in Florida.
</P>
<P>
