<HEADLINE> Namibian Refugees Still in Botswana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The voluntary
repatriation of Namibian separatist refugees from Botswana had not
yet been resumed, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Of the 1,055 Namibians remaining in Botswana's Dukwe refugee
camp, 178 have registered for repatriation, but remain in
Botswana," SAPA quoted Botswanan government spokesman Andrew
Sesinyi as saying.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)
suspended the exercise after the August 2 disturbances in the
Caprivi region of Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Secessionist rebels attacked the major town in Caprivi, Katima
Mulilo, leaving 15 people dead.
</P>
<P>
The Namibians had then cracked down on more members of the
separatist group, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
This led to the arrival in Botswana of 20 more asylum seekers
from the Caprivi.
</P>
<P>
The Namibians in Dukwe were the last of 2,500 separatists who
crossed into Botswana between October and December 1998.
</P>
<P>
They were seeking the secession of the Caprivi from the
Windhoek government and told the Botswana authorities they feared
for their safety as the Namibian Defense Force was moved into the
area.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the UNHCR convention on asylum seekers, to which
both Namibia and Botswana were signatory, the 2,500 people were
granted asylum in Botswana. 
</P>
