<HEADLINE> U.S. Tourists to Tanzania on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa said Friday that the number of U.S. tourists to his
country has kept increasing in recent years.
</P>
<P>
"The number of American tourists coming to Tanzania rose from
14,807 in 1991 to 41,200 last year, 90 percent of whom came for
holiday and game viewing, and 10 percent combined business with
holiday," Mkapa said in Washington D.C. during a working visit to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
According to a copy of his speech made available in Dar es
Salaam, Mkapa said that more and more Americans are getting to
know Tanzanian tourist attractions and the number of those
visiting is rising faster than the global average, a trend which
encourages Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Tanzania has decided to market itself more
vigorously in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzania president revealed that his country is working
together with relevant authorities to promote direct flights from
the United States to Tanzania so that tourists do not have to come
to the east African country through Europe.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania is proud of Kilimanjaro, the highest mountain in
Africa, Ngorongoro Crater, which is described as the "eighth
wonder of the world," and Selous, the largest game reserve in the
world and the oldest in Africa.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the country has an 880-kilometer coastline of
pristine beaches and numerous possibilities for water sports, and
exotic Spice Island of Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
Tourism has become a pillar industry in Tanzania. Last year,
some 482, 000 tourists visited Tanzania, earning the country 570
million U.S. dollars in foreign exchange.  
</P>
</TEXT>
