<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Urges All Parties Concerned to Respect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 17 (xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council on Friday adopted a resolution which urges all
parties concerned to comply strictly with their obligations under
international law and put an end to deliberate targeting of
civilians in situations of armed conflict as well as attacks on
objectives protected under international law.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Security Council held two-day long
debate on measures to protect civilians in armed conflict in
response to a report submitted by Secretary-General Kofi Annan
earlier this week containing recommendations on how the United
Nations could end the practice of targeting innocent
non-combatants.
</P>
<P>
In the resolution, the Security Council strongly condemned the
deliberate targeting by combatants of civilians in armed conflict
and demanded that all parties concerned put an end to such
violations of international humanitarian and human rights law.
</P>
<P>
Emphasizing the importance of preventing conflict which could
endanger international peace and security, the Security Council
highlighted the importance of implementing appropriate preventive
measures to resolve conflicts, including the use of United Nations
and other dispute settlement mechanisms and of preventive military
and civilian deployment, in accordance with the relevant
provisions of the Charter of the United Nations, resolutions of
the Security Council and relevant international instruments.
</P>
<P>
The Council affirmed the need to bring to justice, in an
appropriate manner, individuals who incite or cause violence
against civilians in situations of armed conflict or who otherwise
violate international humanitarian and human rights law.
</P>
<P>
Noting the deleterious impact of the proliferation of arms, in
particular small arms, on the security of civilians, the Council
stressed the importance of all member States, and in particular
States involved in manufacturing and marketing of weapons,
restricting arms transfers which could provoke or prolong armed
conflicts or aggravate existing tensions or armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The Council expressed its willingness to respond to situations
of armed conflict where civilians are being targeted or
humanitarian assistance to civilians is being deliberately
obstructed, including through the consideration of appropriate
measures at the Council's disposal in accordance with the Charter
of the United Nations and the relevant recommendations contained
in the report of the U.N. Secretary-General.
</P>
<P>
The Council decided to establish immediately an appropriate
mechanism to review further the recommendations contained in the
report of the Secretary-General and to consider appropriate steps
by April 2000 in accordance with its responsibilities under the
Charter of the United Nations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
