<HEADLINE> Tanzania Targets Mineral Exports at $337M in 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa Friday came up with an ambitious goal that his
country's mineral exports should reach 337 million U.S. dollars in
three years.
</P>
<P>
"We have put in place a special regime of incentives for the
mining sector that has been acknowledged to be most competitive in
the industry worldwide," Mkapa said during a working visit to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the National Press Club in Washington D.C., Mkapa
said prospecting investments in Tanzania have risen from 630,000
dollars in 1990, to 77.27 million in 1994 and 95.89 million in
1997.
</P>
<P>
"Last year, 57.7 million U.S. dollars, an amount equivalent to
13 percent of Africa's total mineral prospecting budget, were
invested in Tanzania, putting us ahead of even South Africa and
Ghana," Mkapa said in a speech with a copy available in Dar es
Salaam.
</P>
<P>
"We expect that everything being equal, Tanzania's mineral
exports should rise from 22.6 million U.S. dollars to 337.2
million in the year 2002," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president said that Tanzania's gemstone exports have risen
from about 1.5 million dollars in 1990 to 8.1 million last year.
Some 655 million dollars have been invested in the first five gold
mines that should all come on stream in less than five years from
now.
</P>
<P>
Since 1980s, Tanzania has given incentives in taxation to
private investors both at home and abroad to tap its vast mining
potential. Obtaining licenses has also become less difficult.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa welcomed U.S. businessmen to invest in Tanzania, which is
 described by him as a country with political stability,
well-positioned geography, abundant natural resources and
favorable polices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
