<HEADLINE> Internet Engineers Crisis Looming for Europe: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Europe will face an Internet
engineering skills crisis early next century unless more young
people undergo training, warned a new report by the International
Data Corporation (IDC).
</P>
<P>
The report predicted that by 2002, Europe will see a shortfall
of almost 600,000 individuals possessing the fundamental skills to
design, build and manage the networks that are the bedrock of
almost every business and government worldwide.
</P>
<P>
It said that the situation will only worsen unless actions are
taken by European countries to train young people as engineers to
keep pace with the explosive growth of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Among European countries, Germany is predicted to suffer the
most of the engineers crisis with a 31.7 percent shortfall by
2002, the UK ranked second with a 13.8 percent shortage, which is
followed by France, Italy and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Although business has been discussing the skills shortage for
some time, experts said that it is not until now with the
explosive use of the internet that Europe is facing a new crisis
in terms of a networking skills shortage.
</P>
<P>
However, for people willing to learn, the shortage is offering
unprecedented career opportunities, the IDC report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
