<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Trade with U.S. in Encouraging Trend: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa said Friday that although the figures for his
country's trade with the United States are still low but the trend
"is very encouraging."
</P>
<P>
During a working visit to the U.S., Mkapa said exports from
Tanzania rose form 18.8 million U.S. dollars in 1996 to 31.5
million in 1998, an increase of 68 percent in only two years.
These exports for the U.S. were mainly coffee, fish, gemstones and
other precious metals, cotton fabrics and tea.
</P>
<P>
American exports to Tanzania, on the other hand, rose from 50.1
million dollars in 1996 to 66.8 dollars last year, a 33 percent
increase. These included clothing, textiles, information
technology equipment, milk, corn and wheat.
</P>
<P>
"My message during this visit is on the need to increase the
volume of trade both ways and to narrow the trade imbalance,"
Mkapa said at the National Press Club in Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
In a speech with a copy made available in Dar es Salaam, Mkapa
said: "I certainly would appeal for Tanzanian products to be
accepted under a Generalized System of Preferences without much
ado."
</P>
<P>
"Where the trade imbalance cannot be redressed by increased
exports from Tanzania to the U.S., larger investments by American
companies in Tanzania will be helpful, as well as increased number
of American tourists visiting Tanzania," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian president said he had been advised that at
present American investments in Tanzania range 15 million to 20
million dollars a year in sectors such as tourism, manufacturing,
construction, transport, petroleum, fishing and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
"I wish we could make it at least 10 times that amount," he
added. 
</P>
