<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
granted the Southern African Development Community (SADC) 15.2
million U.S. dollars in development aid for the year to September
2000, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
USAid southern African director, Edward Spriggs, and SADC
Executive Secretary Kaire Mbunde Thursday signed agreements
covering five aspects of the U.S./SADC aid program.
</P>
<P>
The largest part of the grant will go to "Regional Activity to
Promote Integration through Dialog and Policy Implementation"
which will get 5.9 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
A "Strategic Objective" agreement, which supports the SADC aim
of a more integrated market in southern Africa, will get 4.8
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
A program to "Strengthen Regional Economies through
Non-governmental Organizations", which will address issues of
democracy and good governance, gets 2.3 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
A further 1.7 million dollars will be spent on "Impact,
Monitoring and Performance" of the overall program, and 549,525
dollars is for program development and support.
</P>
<P>
Later this month, the U.S. and the SADC are expected to sign an
 agreement covering follow-up activity to the First US-SADC Forum
to develop trade and investment, held in Gaborone, Botswana, in
April. The forum was headed by U.S. Undersecretary of State for
Economic Affairs Stuart Eizenstat, and is expected to become an
annual event.
</P>
<P>
The 14 member states of the SADC are: Angola, Botswana, the
Democratic Republic of the Congo, Lesotho, Malawi, Mauritius,
Mozambique, Namibia, Seychelles, South Africa, Swaziland,
Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe. 
