<HEADLINE> Suspected Murderer of British Acquitted in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 17 (Xinhua) --A former senior official of
Kenya Wildlife Service, Simon Makallah, was acquitted Friday of
the horrible murder in 1988 of British tourist Julie Ward in a
national wildlife reserve after a 43-day trial.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of Makallah's fellow Maasai tribe men, dressed in red
shawls and beads, celebrated the acquittal outside the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
John Ward, Julie's father, was stone-faced after hearing the
verdict and said that he wanted a retrial. He had spent about
600,000 U.S. dollars in the past 11 years to hunt the murderer.
</P>
<P>
Judge Daniel Aganyanya said that prosecutors had only offered
circumstantial evidence against Makallah.
</P>
<P>
However, Ward claimed that Makallah had repeatedly talked
privately to the court assessors who advised the judge on the
case.
</P>
<P>
In July the three assessors agreed that the chief warden of
Maasai Mara Wildlife Reserve at the time of the murder was not
guilty. In most cases, judges would follow the advice from
assessors in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Julie, 28 year old then, disappeared in the reserve in
September 9, 1988. Her father came to Kenya the same day and hired
five small planes to comb the national park.
</P>
<P>
Finally, it was Makallah who took her father to the spot where
parts of the charred and mutilated body were found.
</P>
<P>
John said that Makallah had been his chief suspect "from the
first day I saw him". 
</P>
</TEXT>
