<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Emerging Markets in U.S. Create Grand Demand for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 17 (Xinhua) -- There has been a growing
demand in the United States for high-tech battery-powered devices,
according to a market analysis released Friday.
</P>
<P>
The demand is being fueled by the proliferation of wireless
communications tools, photovoltaic applications and
government-supported programs encouraging electric vehicle
markets, said the analysis report from U.S. market research firm
Frost &AMP; Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
There is a growing need for fast charging miniature batteries
and chargers due to the demands of an increasing mobile society,
the report said. The greatest challenge for manufacturers of
miniaturized chargers is to avoid battery overheating. The problem
has been solved by some vendors that develop sophisticated
electronics which automatically switch to a lower charge when the
battery is generating excess heat.
</P>
<P>
The newest addition to the charger industry is the versatile
smart charger, that changes the way it charges depending on
battery type. Smart chargers contain intelligent circuitry that
can recharge batteries much faster than other technologies.
</P>
<P>
In addition to growth in the communication and information
technology industries that is driving the demand for battery
chargers, the report said, there is a potential for growth in
medical applications, such as wheel chairs and scooters, as they
become more user-friendly and as a result of increased demand from
the aging U.S. population.
</P>
<P>
The research firm said that with the constant influx of new
electronic products on the market, products quickly become
obsolete and are replaced by newer, better versions. Therefore
vendors must monitor trends in the marketplace and try to be
always competitive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ITU to Facilitate E-Commerce in Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The International
Telecommunication Union (ITU) and two other organizations have
joined their effort to expand electronic commerce to developing
nations by signing here Friday a Trust Fund partnership
agreement.
</P>
<P>
By the framework to be established under the partnership
agreement, the World Trade Center Geneva will assist the ITU in
expanding the Electronic Commerce in Developing Countries project
(EC-DC) using the World Trade Center network and its global
infrastructure of more than 300 centers in more than 100
countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, a projected 2.7 million U.S. dollars will
be channeled to the Fund every year for the next three years. The
contributions will consist of donations from members of WTC Geneva
and WISeKey, a Swiss company which also joined the partnership.
</P>
<P>
"The advent of the Internet has changed the way we communicate,
conduct business, learn and entertain. But above all, it changed
the way we shop and trade," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must act swiftly and decisively to provide developing
economies with the infocommunication infrastructure needed to join
the digital economy if we do not want to create another form of
development gap," Utsumi added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
