<HEADLINE> Britain Investigates "Landmines on Sale" at Arms Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The British Ministry of
Defense is investigating claims that illegal anti-personnel mines
were on sale this week at a government-supported arms fair, local
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Channel 4 News reported that a Romanian state-owned company was
offering mines, which was declared illegal in Britain, for sale
during the defense Systems and Equipment International(DSEi)
exhibition held currently in Surrey, south-west London.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Ministry of Defense told Channel 4 News all
exhibitors at the show had promised to abide by British law, and
the ministry had vetted publicity material "to ensure compliance".
</P>
<P>
He said the ministry "will investigate the allegations."
</P>
<P>
"If any company has contravened their undertaking then the UK
will vigorously take this up with the proper authorities in the
countries concerned," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shadow Defense Secretary Iain Duncan Smith said he was
"appalled" to hear mines were on sale at the fair, which is
heavily promoted by British Ministry of Defense and the arms
industry.
</P>
<P>
"After lecturing about anti-personnel mines and indeed passing
the Landmines Act in 1998, the government appears less than
vigilant in the UK by allowing these mines to be sold," Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
The possession or sale of the deadly weapons in Britain was
banned under the 1998 Landmines Act, following a campaign
highlighted by the late Princess Diana.
</P>
<P>
The DSEi exhibition was one of the biggest arms fairs in the
world. It was opened by British Defense Secretary George
Robertson on Tuesday and was scheduled to close on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
