<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former FIFA Chief Supports S. Africa for World Cup Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Former FIFA boss Joao
Havelange's support for South Africa's World Cup bid was welcomed
by the South African soccer top brass on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Havelange, who initially stood behind Brazil's bid to host the
World Cup in 2006, this week made a surprise about-turn when he
called on his country to withdraw its candidature and support the
South African bid instead.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, England, Germany and Morocco are all in the race with
South Africa to host the prestigious tournament in 2006.
</P>
<P>
The South Africa Bid Committee chief executive Danny Jordaan
said Havelange's backing would prove a major boost to this country
's campaign and if Brazil had to pull out it would leave the race
strictly between Africa and Europe.
</P>
<P>
"If that happens it would now be between Africa and Europe to
win the bid," Jordaan said. "Havelange has always been supportive
of the idea that the global character of the game be entrenched
and he has shown this with the development of many of FIFA's
competitions under his presidency.
</P>
<P>
"For years he has been saying that the game should be universal
and his message is a massive boost to us.
</P>
<P>
"We have now received the backing for our bid of the three most
powerful men in the world sports. Already FIFA president Sepp
Blatter has come out in favour of our candidature and now
Havelange.
</P>
<P>
"Last week, the International Olympic Committee president Juan
Antonio Samaranch also gave us his backing at the start of the All-
Africa Games. We now have great heart and courage thanks to their
support," Jordaan said.
</P>
<P>
Jordaan felt that the hitches encountered in the All-Africa
Games would not in anyway affect the country's World Cup bid.
</P>
<P>
"We will sit down with the All-Africa Games authorities and
make a review of the Games. The Games are a mix of all different
sporting codes, while the World Cup is only about soccer. No, I
don't think the problems in the Games will affect our bid at all,"
Jordaan said.
</P>
<P>
Havelange said this week that Brazil's poor infrastructure
would harm its chances of getting the nod and felt pulling out now
would enhance the South Americans' hopes for 2010.
</P>
<P>
"I prefer to lose a finger than a hand. To win, you have to
know how to lose. If Brazil doesn't hold the Cup in 2006, I can
guarantee it will in 2010," he reportedly said.
</P>
<P>
Supporting an African bid would ensure the continent's four
votes would come to Brazil when the the world body names the 2010
host. If Brazil got the four votes from Asia and six from the
Americas, it would have enough to beat a bid from Europe, who have
eight votes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
