<HEADLINE> Individuals In China "Adopting" Pandas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 18 (Xinhua) -- A 2-year-old panda at a
giant panda breeding institute in Chengdu, capital of southwest
China's Sichuan province, was adopted by a private company today.
</P>
<P>
Xie Silin, the owner of a non-ferrous steel products company in
Chao'an County in Guangdong Province, south China., donated 800,
000 yuan (about 100,000 U.S. dollars) to the institute to help
raise the giant panda for 20 years, becoming a "nursing father" in
the process.
</P>
<P>
Xie explained the generous offer by saying that, in the course
of business development, they destroy the environment and he
wanted to do something of his own to protect the environment.
</P>
<P>
The 547-mu (about 36-hectare) giant panda institute is in the
northern suburbs of Chengdu and is the only institute of its kind
in China. It cost 80 million yuan to build, half of that coming
from contributions from China and abroad. It has 27 giant pandas,
13 of which have been adopted in a similar way.  
</P>
</TEXT>
