<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek, Cyprus Defense Ministers Meet in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Defense Ministers of Greece
and Cyprus held talks here Saturday and both sides reconfirmed the
joint defense policy between their two countries.
</P>
<P>
Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos and his visiting
Cyprus counterpart, Sokratis Hasikou, discussed the further
support of the existing defense policies, cooperation in military
training and equipment, and the European prospect of the island
republic, which has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and occupied the northern third of Cyprus in the wake of a
failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after their talks, Tsohatzopoulos said that the better
climate created by the recent earthquakes in Turkey and Greece did
not influence the policy of securing stability and defense
capability. The defense strategy was influenced only by the
development of political and realistic elements, he added.
</P>
<P>
The joint military exercise would take place as scheduled from
October 2 to 7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
