<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Government to Aid Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The British Ministry of
Agriculture has confirmed that the government is to announce a new
aid package, worth around 80 million pounds (about 128 million
U.S. dollars), for cash-strapped cattle and sheep farmers in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Officials are putting the final touches to the package this
weekend and it is likely to be announced on Monday afternoon,
according to a BBC report.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the new subsidy is to help meet the cost of "red
tape" regulations which UK farmers say is adding to the price of
beef and lamb and making UK meat uncompetitive.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman said the new aid, to apply to farmers in England,
Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland, was fresh money and it would
help meet the extra costs imposed on farmers before sending their
animals to abbatoirs.
</P>
<P>
There would also be money to help meet the cost of the passport
scheme for beef cattle which was imposed in the wake of BSE. But
it was not clear yet whether the scheme would apply to pigs as
well as cattle and sheep.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said this aid was aimed at reimbursing farmers
for the bureaucratic burdens which had been imposed on them.
</P>
<P>
The question of whether there should be help to buy up unwanted
sheep and other animals, as proposed by the Scottish and Welsh
Parliaments - was separate.
</P>
<P>
Nick Brown, the agriculture minister, was waiting to hear
details from the farming ministers in Edinburgh and Cardiff and
would then take it up with the European Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
