<HEADLINE> Chinese Strongmen Are Climbing up Tough Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WEINAN, SHAANXI, China, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese
young strongmen do make their impacts in the fourth Chinese City
Games but are still climbing up a tough road for great feats in
the world.
</P>
<P>
As the weightlifting competitions concluded here on Saturday,
the strongmen aged under 20 surpassed three world junior marks by
three persons in eight categories.
</P>
<P>
Besides, two Asian junior records were attacked and six
national junior marks were set up in the City Games with all the
competitions to be concluded on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Shi Zhiyong, a 19-year-old teenager from Xiamen, Fujian
province, surpassed two world junior records in the 62-kg category.
</P>
<P>
"I just hope to win the gold medal in the 2000 Olympic Games,
and to improve my skills to lift a two-lift total of 330 kgs,"
said the young strongman.
</P>
<P>
However, the concerned Chinese sports authorities are well
aware of the dire fact that no breakthrough was ever made in the
heavy classes as the City Games failed to produce any successor
for Cui Wenhua.
</P>
<P>
"Although five strongmen broke three national junior marks,
their winning results lag far behind the world bests by a huge
margin," said Qian Guangjian, secretary general of the Chinese
Weightlifting Association.
</P>
<P>
"And the worst nagging problem is the lack of future stars with
potentials as Shi Zhiyong, Guo Guan and Wu Qinghua all compete in
the smaller categories of either 62kg or 69kg classes," said the
official.
</P>
<P>
As a sport dated back to ancient Greece, weightlifting offers
eight gold medals for the strongmen in the Olympic Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
