<HEADLINE> Lebanon Opens Presidential Palace to Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon opened 32 historical
and prominent sites, including the presidential palace, to the
public on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In the day, Lebanese President Emile Lahoud greeted and shook
hands with thousands of visitors in the Baabda Palace, which was
built in 1965 in the northern suburban of Beirut,
</P>
<P>
The public was allowed into the president's office, residential
quarters and gardens for the first time.
</P>
<P>
"It is very exciting for me as a ordinary person to visit the
presidential palace and I am very proud that our country has such
a grand official complex," a 23-year university student told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Besides the presidential palace, the Grand Serail, or the
Ottoman-era prime ministry palace, and the newly renovated
Parliament building were also open to the public for free this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
The event, labeled "Days of Heritage and Nationalism", was part
of a drive by the Ministry of Culture to stimulate interests in
Lebanon's historical sites and landmarks. 
</P>
