<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Ails Farm Production in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(By Chen Qiaoyan)
</P>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Agricultural production has
been affected in Sub-Saharan Africa as increasing number of
farmers die of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released at the 11th International
Conference on AIDS and STDS (sexually transmitted diseases) in
Africa in Lusaka, the HIV/ AIDS pandemic is not only a health
issue, but also a serious problem for development in general.
</P>
<P>
HIV/AIDS has severely reduced the active production force in
the labor intensive agriculture sector, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In Zambia, maize output in some provinces fell by over 30
percent during 1997/1998 season.
</P>
<P>
Although lack of inputs and climatic conditions were partly to
blame for this decline, AIDS-related loss of labor attributed
largely to the reduction of output.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released by Joint United Nations Program
on HIV/ AIDS (UNAIDS) and World Health Organization, it is
estimated that in 1998, 7o percent of newly infected with HIV, the
virus which causes AIDS, live in Sub-Saharan Africa. And 83
percent of AIDS deaths have taken place in the region, which
accounts for only one-tenth of the world population, since the
epidemic started.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, it is estimated that there were about 21.5
million adults and one million children infected with HIV in black
Africa.
</P>
<P>
A FAO study found that the commercial agriculture sector of
Kenya is particularly vulnerable to the epidemic and is facing a
severe social and economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
After studying the impacts, FAO is moving into a new phase of
examining the possible responses from the agricultural sector to
the epidemic. And it will jointly with UNAIDS issue a report,
which is entitled "The Sustainable Agricultural, Rural Development
and Vulnerability to HIV/AIDS."
</P>
<P>
The organization suggests that these challenges have to be
taken into account when outlining and implementing agricultural
and rural development programs in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0096 </DOCNO>
