<HEADLINE> Chinese President Provides Calligraphy for Sino-Japan Cultural Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin has
done the calligraphy for a cultural exchange with Japan and the
largest series of Chinese performances and exhibition in Japan
since the two countries established diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
The '99 Visit to Japan is made up of performances by the
Beijing Opera, the Chinese Symphony Orchestra, and an exhibition
on China over the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
The series of cultural activities coincide with the 50th
anniversary of the People's Republic of China and the 20th
anniversary of the Sino-Japanese cultural exchange agreement.
</P>
<P>
Increasing bilateral cultural exchanges and friendship between
the two peoples is very important, Jiang said, and extended his
heart-felt congratulations in the calligraphy. He also said he
believes that the visit by famous Chinese artists will play a
positive role in promoting friendly cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi also wrote an inscription
for the event and expressed his congratulations and said that
cultural exchanges further demonstrate their importance in
enhancing mutual understanding. 
