<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three European Cyclists Banned for Failing Blood Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Three European cycling
competitors were thrown out of races in France and Italy for
failing blood tests.
</P>
<P>
Belgium's Marc Streel was prevented from starting the Grand
Prix des Nations at Forges-les-Eaux in western France after a test
showed his red corpsucle count to be above the International
Cycling Union safety limit of 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
28-year-old Streel, who rides for Danish team Home Jack and
Jones, will not be able to race for 15 days.
</P>
<P>
Two Italian cyclists, Fulvio Frigo and Giacomo Cariulo, were
similarly prevented from competing in the Tour of Latium in Italy
after they returned blood readings above the safety limit.
</P>
<P>
Former Tour de France and Tour of Italy champion Marco Pantani
was a high-profile victim of the blood-testing regulations in July
when he was thrown out of the Tour of Italy for showing a red
corpsucle count of 52 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
