<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Acquire Four Larger Destroyers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Defense Agency decided
Saturday on a plan to acquire four new destroyers for the Maritime
Self-Defense Force (MSDF), Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, Kyodo quoted agency sources as saying, the MSDF
's four current 5,000-ton class flagships will be upgraded to 10,
000-ton class destroyers starting from the next midterm defense
plan of fiscal 2001 to 2005.
</P>
<P>
The move is aimed at improving Japan's ability "to respond to
emergencies in unspecified areas surrounding Japan," the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The four 5,000-ton class destroyers to be phased out are each
equipped with three antisubmarine helicopters, and 5-inch and 20-
millimeter guns.
</P>
<P>
They will be replaced by larger destroyers with multipurpose
helicopters equipped with transport functions, ability to
accommodate more people, and advanced communications functions
using satellite linkups toward further strengthening liaisons and
joint cooperation with the U.S. military, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
All four flagships are to be phased out within the next 10
years, with two of them expected to be retired during the next
midterm defense plan, they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
