<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sculpture Set Up in HK to Mark Victory of Anti-Japanese War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Various commemoration
activities were held in Hong Kong Saturday to mark the day when
Japan launched the aggression war against China 68 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Among these activities, an inauguration ceremony of the
establishment of a bronze sculpture of "Fighters Defending the
Motherland" at the Sai Kung East Country Park in the New
Territories was accompanied by a chorus composed of songs
reminding people of the days when China was invaded by foreign
imperialists.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Lo, executive director of the construction committee of the
sculpture, said at the inauguration ceremony that it is of great
significance to set up this sculpture to cherish the memory of
those who died for defending the motherland when people throughout
the Chinese mainland and Hong Kong celebrate the 50th anniversary
of the founding of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
The sculpture to be set up in Hong Kong is one of the total 38
bronze ones made by artists in Beijing. It depicts the brilliant
deeds of the compatriots in Hong Kong and Macao who fought against
the Japanese aggressors during the war, according to Lo.
</P>
<P>
The chorus was founded in Hong Kong in early 1939 and
reorganized in Guangzhou in 1984. It is composed of 100 singers,
most of them aged over 65.  
</P>
</TEXT>
