<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Praises Nuclear Scientists (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin praised
the Chinese scientists who made the country's first atomic bomb, H-
bomb, and satellites in the 60s and early 70s, at a commendation
meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the scholars and scientists helped strengthen
China's scientific and defense capability and helped lay the
cornerstone of China's global position through their untiring
efforts over several generations. China has become one of the few
countries with independent knowledge of nuclear and space
technology and is setting the pace in some key technological
fields, he said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was sponsored by the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC), the State Council, and the Central
Military Commission (CMC) and presided over by Li Peng, the
chairman of the National People's Congress Standing Committee.
Premier Zhu Rongji made the announcement to hold the meeting to
commend 23 experts, seven of whom are deceased and one of whom is
in hospital.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, also general secretary of the CPC Central Committee and
chairman of the CMC, conferred the meritorious services medals in
person to the 15 scientists who were present at the meeting. He
said that the decision to develop nuclear weapons and satellites
was made by Mao Zedong in the 50s and 60s to counter the extortion
and monopoly of nuclear power by some major countries and to boost
China's defense capability and safeguard world peace.
</P>
<P>
He quoted Deng Xiaoping as saying that without atomic warheads
and the H-bomb or its own satellite, China could not have become a
major country with important influence or have attained the
international status it has today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Praises Nuclear Scientists (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China detonated its first atomic bomb on October 16, 1964 and
fired its first ground-to-ground missile with a nuclear warhead on
October 27, 1966. On June 17, 1967, it exploded its first nuclear
bomb in the air, and on April 24, 1970, it launched its first
satellite. Jiang said that these were scientific miracles that
took place under fragile material and technological conditions.
</P>
<P>
He named five important principles learned from this that
should still be followed:
</P>
<P>
-- Upholding unified leadership of the CPC and giving full play
to the political advantages of socialism in China;
</P>
<P>
-- Self-reliance and creativity in science and technology
exploration and actively learning key technology from foreign
countries;
</P>
<P>
-- Trying to do certain things and not doing others and
focusing on development of new and high technology and science;
</P>
<P>
-- Greater investment in education and technology and experts
being paid more respect; and
</P>
<P>
-- Making an effort to improve management for quality and
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Jiang stressed the implementation of the strategy of
rejuvenating the country through science and education. He asked
Chinese scientists to keep abreast of international research
developments and to cultivate a new generation of experts and
talented people to contribute to the economic development and
national security of China.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the meeting along with 6,000 people from
various walks of life were the other members of the Standing
Committee of the Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee Li
Ruihuan, Hu Jintao, Wei Jianxing and Li Lanqing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
