<HEADLINE> HK to Do More to Help Victims of Domestic Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government would examine how to
improve services to victims of domestic violence to help them
rebuild their lives and integrate into the society.
</P>
<P>
The SAR's Administrative Secretary Anson Chan Saturday had a
meeting with groups of victims of domestic violence, and
representatives of non-governmental organizations providing
services and assistance to these victims.
</P>
<P>
"I want to gain a better understanding of the plight and
difficulties faced by victims of domestic violence, and to see
what further measures the government can take to help this
unfortunate group," Chan said.
</P>
<P>
There was a detailed and open exchange of views at the meeting
where representatives of the victim groups and the non-
governmental organizations made various suggestions on possible
improvements to service delivery.
</P>
<P>
There was also a suggestion that more attention should be paid
to assist women who were victims of sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
While expressing sympathy to the victims, Chan said she was
also encouraged by the fact that some of the victims were able to
overcome their past traumatic experience and to rebuild their
lives through the assistance of the voluntary organizations.
</P>
<P>
"The government will look into the suggestions raised during
the meeting to see how best to improve the services provided to
these victims," Chan said.  
</P>
