<HEADLINE> Chinese Teenager Swimmer Surpasses Asian Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, China, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese teenager Qi Hui
surpassed an Asian record to take the women's 200-meter
breaststroke in the fourth Chinese City Games here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Qi Hui, born on January 13, 1985, clocked 2:26.51 against the
Asian mark of 2:26.65 set up by a Japanese swimmer, the first-ever
feat attained by the Chinese swimmers in the City Games.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very glad to win the title with an Asian mark," said the
14-year-old teenager, "I thought of breaking the national mark in
the Games as I am in my top form these days."
</P>
<P>
"My winning timing of an Asian mark will push me for more
titles in the international arena in the coming years as it will
be both a pressure and an impetus for me to achieve better results
in the future," said Qi Hui.
</P>
<P>
With her personal best of 2:28.79, Qi Hui is currently ranked
fifth in the world in the discipline.
</P>
<P>
Qi Hui began her swimming career at the age of seven when she
joined a training class in the Taijiang district in Fuzhou, and
was later recruited into the municipal and provincial squads
within two years.
</P>
<P>
In March, 1995, Qi Hui became the double champion in the 50m
and 100m breaststrokes in the national swimming championships for
children.
</P>
<P>
In May 1998, she triumphed in the 200m breaststroke in the
national champions swimming meet and finished second in the same
discipline in the national swimming championships in last October.
</P>
<P>
In the Bangkok Asian Games last December, Qi Hui finished
runner-up in the 200m breaststroke before taking the 200m
breaststroke title in the Beijing stop of the World short-course
swimming championships in January, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
