<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Conference for Gurkhas Opens in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 18 (Xinhua) -- An international conference
for equal rights to Gurkha soldiers who served in the British army
began in Kathmandu Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The conference began with a mass rally of about 30,000
ex-Gurkha soldiers and their families who paraded four kilometers
from the neighboring Lalitpur to Kathmandu.
</P>
<P>
At the three-day conference, the plight of retired Gurkha
soldiers from the British army and their families will be
discussed and participants will look for ways for their demands
for equal treatment and pensions to be satisfied.
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of the conference is to raise international
attention for the plight of retired Gurkha soldiers and their
families and to demand equal rights as the British soldiers, said
Yam Bahadur Gurung, general secretary of the central committee of
the Gurkha Army Ex. Servicemen Organization (GAESO).
</P>
<P>
"This is the first international conference of the kind, as we
have invited delegates from 37 countries, such as Britain, Sweden,
Germany, America, Russia, Portugal, India, and so on," said
Gurung, who served in the British army from 1969 to 1979 and was a
lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
Some of the delegates are lawyers, historians, human rights
activists , anthropologists, he said.
</P>
<P>
GAESO has been pushing for equal pensions for retired Gurkha
soldiers for the past five years. It has put forward four demands
for them: pensions for all former Gurkha soldiers who were sent
back without any pensions; equal pensions with their British
counterparts; residential visas for Britain and arrangement of
education and employment for the half-educated children of former
Gurkha soldiers.
</P>
<P>
GAESO said that according to official estimates of the British
government, about 450,000 Nepali soldiers had fought for Britain
during the First and Second World Wars, and 2,500 to 3,000 Nepali
soldiers are still serving in the British army.
</P>
<P>
After retirement, a British soldier receives 760 U.S. dollars
per month, but his Nepalese counterpart gets only 32 dollars per
month. Some Gurkha soldiers who fought during the two world wars
were sent home even without any pension.
</P>
<P>
"We are not begging, we are just seeking for equal rights,"
said Gurung.
</P>
<P>
All those who took part in the rally held a sign with slogans
on it. Some of them read: "We want justice for living." "Stop
discriminations against the Gurkhas." "We want equal rights from
the British government."
</P>
<P>
The British army started to draft Gurkhas in 1816 under the
Sugauli Treaty signed between Nepal and the East India Company of
Britain. Altogether 15,000 Gurkha soldiers have been killed in
wars so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0129 </DOCNO>
