<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Auriol Steps into Driving Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUAIROU, Beijing, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Frenchman Didier
Auriol drove his Toyota into a 10.7-second advantage after 16
stages in the China Rally on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Auriol, who is second in the world championship following Tommi
Makinen, took up the front running at the end of the second leg of
the rally with only six much easier stages left in the 11th round
of the World Rally Championship.
</P>
<P>
The major drama of the day was the retirement of world champion
Makinen who stopped his Mitsubishi in the final stage of the day
with suspension failure.
</P>
<P>
Overnight leader Briton Richard Burns of Subaru remains in
second place, a comfortable 48.6 seconds ahead of the second
Toyota Corolla driven by Spaniard Carlos Sainz.
</P>
<P>
Juha Kankkunen, also from Subaru, is a distant fourth almost
four minutes behind the leader and in turn 1:30.6 ahead of his
fellow Finn Harri Rovanpera in a SEAT.
</P>
<P>
Auriol finished the day with his heart beating just a little
bit faster than at the start.
</P>
<P>
"The last stage was just unbelievable," he said. "It was so
slippery - you could be in sixth gear at 180kmh and try to brake
and the car just wouldn't slow down, it kept sliding and sliding.
</P>
<P>
"It happended many times and was very difficult on the heart.
It was a nightmare. I never want to do that again."
</P>
<P>
Makinen, who is seeking for his fourth straight world win, had
moved back into third place before that stage and looked ready to
mount a strong challenge on the final day.
</P>
<P>
The Finn was clearly the quickest driver on the day with four
fastest times before his demise, but his 10-point advantage on the
drivers championship could have been completely cut off if Auriol
would have won the China Rally.
</P>
<P>
Burns and Sainz shared the remaining benchmarks with speeds
much higher than on day one.
</P>
<P>
Over half the starting field have now succumbed to the rough
roads and bad weather as the rally has announced 37 retirements so
far, with 30 cars still running.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Toshihiro Arai of Subaru led the Group N field by 29.7
seconds from Hamed Al Wahaibi of Oman with Gustavo Trelles of
Uraguay a distant third. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
