<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Advance Team of U.N. Force to Arrive in E.Timor Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- A 13-member advance team of
the United Nations multinational force is scheduled to arrive on
Sunday in Dili, capital of East Timor, Antara news agency reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with Antara, Chief of the Military
Operational Command in East Timor Maj. Gen. Kiki Sjahnakri said
the advance team and the martial law authority will discuss the
arrival and the task of the main body of the U.N. force.
</P>
<P>
The team had been scheduled to arrive in Dili on Saturday, but
the U.N. has delayed its arrival.
</P>
<P>
Kiki said the fact that both the Indonesian Military (TNI) and
the U.N. had yet to agree on the cooperation scheme might have
caused the delay.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to create a conducive climate prior to the arrival of
a multinational force in Dili, the martial law authority in East
Timor has continued seizing guns from pro-integrationist groups,
Antara said.
</P>
<P>
Streets in Dili remained deserted on Saturday, as arson and
looting committed by refugees and unarmed members of pro-autonomy
groups again erupted in several parts of Dili, Antara said, adding
that security personnel were forced to open fire in the air to
drive away the arsonists and the looters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the plan to drop food supplies from airplanes agreed
to by TNI, the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and the
International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC) has not been
started due to technical problems.
</P>
<P>
TNI, the UNHCR and the ICRC had yet to find the right place to
drop the food deliveries for East Timorese taking refuge in safer
places, Kiki said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
