<HEADLINE> Multinational Force's Warships Leave for East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Nine warships left
Australia's northern harbor of Darwin Saturday in two groups to
take up positions off East Timor, AAP reported, quoting a defense
force spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The first group, spearheaded by Australian navy ship Adelaide,
a guided-missile frigate, also includes another three Australian
vessels --a frigate, a supply ship and a heavy-lift amphibious
vessel.
</P>
<P>
Three Australian landing crafts were in the second group which
is headed by British destroyer HMS Glasgow.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the New Zealand frigate Te Kaha was
among the nine warships.
</P>
<P>
The ships would remain poised off the waters of East Timor
until troops and materiel on board were given the go-ahead to
deploy in the East Timor land.
</P>
<P>
No details were immediately available on how many personnel or
what kind of materiel were on board the nine ships.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Australia has said it expects a contingent of about
2,000 soldiers to depart from Darwin for East Timor Sunday or
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The multinational force commanded by an Australian major
general was authorized by the U.N. security council to carry out a
peacekeeping mission in East Timor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
