<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unfancied Liu Guozheng Wins Men's Singles Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, China, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Last minute substitute
Liu Guozheng became the revelation of the '99 China Grand Prix
Table Tennis Championships as the unfancied Chinese paddler won
the men's singles title here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Liu, entering the tournament as the understudy of injury-hit
former world champion Kong Linhui, toughed out a 21-11, 17-21, 12-
21, 21-15, 21-19 victory over South Korean Lee Chul Seung in the
final and pocketed 12,500 U.S. dollars prize money.
</P>
<P>
It was the first major title for Liu, one of the unsung heroes
from the star-studded Chinese men's squad, and it came the hard
way.
</P>
<P>
He took the biggest scalp of the tournament by eliminating his
world champion teammate Liu Guoliang, who he is not related to
though they bear similar names, in the third round, before
overcoming another glamour Chinese compatriot Wang Liqin, ITTF Pro-
Tour finals winner, in the semi-finals earlier today.
</P>
<P>
"Today is a very important day in my career," said the jubilant
player, "Finally I translated my training efforts into a major
title."
</P>
<P>
Liu Guozheng revealt that he had an impressive record against
Liu Guoliang in the training camp but lack of strong nerves at
crucial moments often cost him in the big events.
</P>
<P>
But the absence of top European players, especially Sweden's
Jan-ove Waldner, Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus and Croatian Zoran
Primorac, made Liu's triumph less convincing in a depleted men's
singles field.
</P>
<P>
In the following men's doubles final, Chinese duo Wang Liqin/
Yan Sen thrashed the South Korean pair Kim Taek Soo/Oh Sang Eun 21-
15, 21-19 to take the gold and ensure the host nation make it four
out of four in an another major tournament.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Chinese world number three Li Ju scored a walk-
over victory over Chinese-born German Qianhong Gotsch, who quit
the final due to a fever after a gutsy four-set win over world
champion and top seed Wang Nan in the semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
Li Nan and Lin Ling toppled the world championships-winning
combination Wang Nan and Li Ju to claim the women's doubles title.
</P>
<P>
Last month China swept the board at the 45th table tennis world
championships, bagging home all five gold and silver medals on
offer.
</P>
<P>
The China Grand Prix, an ITTF Pro-Tour event, officially came
to end here today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
