<HEADLINE> Auriol Overtakes Burns on Top, Makinen Retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUAIROU, Beijing, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Frenchman Didier
Auriol stole the leading place from Richard Burns of Britain after
16 stages on Saturday, while world leader Tommi Makinen of Finland
pulled out of the rally because of the suspension failure in the
China Rally here.
</P>
<P>
The overnight leader Burns, a Subaru, kept his top place in the
first four stages of the day before Auriol, a Toyota, stormed into
the driving position with a 12.8 seconds lead over the Briton
after the last four.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi's Makinen, three-consecutive-time world champion,
pulled out of the rally on the stage 16 with a broken suspension
when he was at the third place behind Auril and Burns.
</P>
<P>
Spaniard Carlos Sainz, driving a Toyota, was on third, trailing
the leader by almost one minute, while another Subaru, Juha
Kankkunen of Finland was further back at fourth.
</P>
<P>
There are six stages left in the China Rally on the final day
on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Havelange: Brazil Should Back South Africa in World Cup Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAO PAULO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Former FIFA President Joao
Havelange has obviously changed his mind as he voiced out his
support to South Africa in its bid for hosting the 2006 World Cup
finals.
</P>
<P>
Havelange, who had been one of the main supporters of the
Brazilian bid, said his country's lack of infrastructure hurt its
chances. South Africa, Morocco, Germany and England are other
bidding sides for soccer's quadrennial championship.
</P>
<P>
"I would like the 2006 Cup to be in South Africa and the
following one in Brazil," Havelange was quoted at a ceremony
Thursday to promote an international congress for soccer-related
businesses.
</P>
<P>
Heading FIFA for more than two decades, Havelange was
considered a key lobbyist for Brazil's bid. However, he said his
reversal was simply for increasing Brazil's chances of succeding
in getting the Cup in 2010.
</P>
<P>
"I prefer to lose a finger than a hand. To win, you have to
know how to lose," he was quoted as saying. "If Brazil doesn't
hold the Cup in 2006, I can guarantee it will in 2010."
</P>
<P>
Havelange suggests that supporting an African bid now will
ensure the continent's four votes when the FIFA Executive
Committee choses the 2010 host.
</P>
<P>
If Brazil also gets all four votes from Asia and six from the
Americas, it would virtually assure itself a bid from Europe,
which has eight votes.
</P>
<P>
However, the Asian Football Confederation have irked some in
South America by publicly arguing that CONMEBOL should give up its
half berth in the 2002 finals to Asia.
</P>
<P>
Asia had been demanding five full berths and the half from
South America along with a half offered by Europe would have met
that demand. The AFC and FIFA president Sepp Blatter last week
signed an agreement in which the Asian confederation agreed to its
4 1-2 berths without further threatening to boycott the event's
qualifiers rounds.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is the only country in the world to win the tournament
four times. The 2002 World Cup will be jointly staged by Japan
and South Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
