<HEADLINE> Australian Swimmer Awarded in Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- With President Fidel Castro's
presence, Cuba on Friday awarded Australian woman swimmer Susie
Maroney a "heroine of world sport" for completing marathon swims
to and from the Caribbean island.
</P>
<P>
Maroney, 24, received the title in a special ceremony attended
by Cuban government officlas, just days after finishing an
exhausting swimming odyssey of more than 35 hours from Jamaica to
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
It was her third swim of more than 145 kilometers in the last
few years. She had previously crossed from Cuba to the United
States in 1996 and from Mexico to Cuba in 1998.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony in Havana's Palace of the Revolution, the
Australian swimmer received a special certificate from Cuba's
Council of State, which described her an "extraordinary heroine of
world sport" for her brave swims.
</P>
<P>
Castro presented her with the certificate, planting a kiss on
both her cheeks.
</P>
<P>
"I am very honoured to be here. I am overwhelmed with
everybody's kindness," Maroney said after receiving the award. "I
fell in love with Cuba in 1996 when I first attempted Cuba to the
United States. The water was so blue and beautiful," she added.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban president had designed and donated the shark cage
that protected the swimmer during her latest crossing from Montego
Bay, Jamaica to Marea del Portillo beach in Cuba's eastern Granma
Province.
</P>
<P>
The Australian completed her latest swim Tuesday despite waves
whipped up by the passage of Hurricane Floyd, early damage to the
shark-cage, and numerous jelly-fish stings. "I love the challenge,
pushing my body," she said.
</P>
<P>
Cuban swimmer Rodolfo Falcon, a two-time Olympic champion, read
a tribute to Maroney praising both her feats in the water and
achievements as a humanitarian campaigner for various health
causes such as leukaemia victims and the disabled.
</P>
<P>
Senior Cuban sports' officials presented Maroney with three
trophies for the crossings. The ceremony was broadcast live
across Cuba on state TV. 
</P>
</TEXT>
