<HEADLINE> New UNFICYP Caretaker Chief Appointed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides has announced that Chilean James Holger will be the
caretaker chief of the U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP).
</P>
<P>
Clerides made the announcement upon his arrival in New York on
Thursday night to the attend the 54th session of the U.N. General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Holger has served with the U.N. in Cyprus in the past and Dame
Ann Hercus, who has resigned as UNFICYP chief for personal
reasons, will leave at the end of the month, the Cyprus Mail
newspaper reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Holger will be the caretaker chief until former Norwegian
Foreign Minister Jan Egland is appointed UNFICYP chief.
</P>
<P>
Hercus, from New Zealand, launched on-island contacts with
Cyprus' two sides last October with a view to make progress
towards the reduction of tensions and a settlement to Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish Troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island with
a bi-communal federation formula, but the talks between the two
rival sides have been stalled since 1997.
</P>
<P>
The UNFICYP was established in 1964 and the 1,200-strong
peacekeepers are patroling the 180-kilometer line dividing the two
rival sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
