<HEADLINE> Estrada Says Marcoses Have No Deal to Call off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said Saturday that the family of the late President
Ferdinand Marcos could not have backed off from a compromise deal
with his administration, as there is no deal to speak of in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
In a weekly program aired over the People's Television here,
Estrada stressed that all agreements involving the Marcoses should
go through the Presidential Commission on Good Government (PCGG)
headed by former Justice Magdangal Elma.
</P>
<P>
"In the first place, how can they call off a deal that does not
exist?" the president said.
</P>
<P>
The president was reacting to reports that the Marcoses had
withdrawn from a 75-25 percent share deal supposedly worked out
with the government in its efforts to recover the alleged
ill-gotten Marcos wealth.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted an unnamed relative of the Marcoses as
saying the deal was cut off since President Estrada could not
"defend" his decision to enter into a compromise settlement with
them.
</P>
<P>
"There is no agreement to defend. How can we defend it when
there is no agreement to speak of?" Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he has already assured former President Corazon
Aquino that the government will not enter into an agreement with
the Marcoses on their alleged ill-gotten wealth.
</P>
<P>
He said that Elma, a former executive secretary and trusted
ally of Corazon Aquino, would be the first to know about any deal
with the Marcoses because this would have to go through him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
