<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Strives for Quality Assurance in Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The schools, the community
and the Education Department of Hong Kong were called Saturday to
concert their efforts to achieve the target of providing quality
education.
</P>
<P>
The remark came at a ceremony to grant certificates of
appreciation to 18 seconded school heads and teachers and 39 lay
members in recognition of their contribution to the Quality
Assurance Inspection (QAI).
</P>
<P>
The Education Department has been adopting a whole school
approach to school inspection, the QAI, since the 1997/98 school
year.
</P>
<P>
The QAI involves several domains of school education, such as
management and organization, teaching and learning, school ethos
and support for students.
</P>
<P>
In addition to professional staff from the ED, experienced
front-line educators and lay members are invited to participate in
the QAI team.
</P>
<P>
Addressing Saturday's ceremony, Fanny Law, director of
education, stressed that the participation of the front-line
educators and lay members was important to the success of QAI.
</P>
<P>
"Now that 19 per cent of the government's annual expenditure is
invested on education and the public is increasingly concerned
over the effectiveness of school education, it is imperative for
us to develop a thorough mechanism of quality assurance which
encourages accountability," she said.
</P>
<P>
Also officiating at the ceremony, William Lo, chairman of the
Advisory Committee on QAI, reported on the latest development of
the QAI.
</P>
<P>
Ever since its implementation, responses from the schools
inspected have been generally positive.
</P>
<P>
Schools are able to identify their strengths and possible areas
for improvement by participating in the highly transparent QAI
exercise. They can eventually engage themselves successfully in
self-evaluation and self-improvement.
</P>
<P>
"Experience sharing and dissemination of good practice among
schools, encouraging school self-evaluation and identifying areas
of school improvement would be the main focus for this year's
training and publicity activities," Lo said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Education Department would lay emphasis on
offering post-inspection support and guidance to schools that need
improvement.
</P>
<P>
The Education Department has collated the information on the
performances of 46 schools inspected in the 1998/1999 school year
and produced an annual summary report on QAI for schools'
reference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
