<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Trade Deficit Reaches Five-year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon brought its trade
deficit to a five-year low of 3.67 billion U.S. dollars during
the first eight months of 1999, the Daily Star reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Exports climbed to a six-year high of 480 million dollars, or
12.4 percent higher than the 427 million dollars recorded last
year, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Imports, on the other hand, fell to a five-year low of just
4.15 billion dollars over the same period.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fall in imports, Customs duties still brought in
942 million dollars in revenues, a 7 percent rise over the 881
million dollars in tariffs collected during the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Jewlery worth 72 million dollars was Lebanon's number one
export followed by machinery and mechanical appliances valued at
60 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In third place were base metals worth some 52 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Machinery and mechanical appliances took the top spot for
imports, amounting to 630 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Cars and other vehicles came in at 409 million dollars, a
distant second and chemical products followed closely behind at
389 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Re-exports reached 48 million dollars, representing an increase
of 9 percent over last year's 44 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Transiting goods were down 10.25 percent from 39 million
dollars in 1998 to 35 million dollars in the first eight months of
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
