<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Drafts Children's Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Children's Bill has been
drafted and will be submitted to parliament by the end of this
year, Kenya's Attorney General Amos Wako said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the third African Conference on Child Abuse and
Neglect, Wako said that the bill is designed to promote children's
rights in Kenya, according to Saturday's Daily Nation.
</P>
<P>
Wako said that the government had ratified the United Nations
Convention on the Rights of the Children and that the African
Charter on the Rights of the Children would be approved as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
"If issues relating to children's welfare are not addressed
now, the countries in Africa, including Kenya, have no hope," said
Wako.
</P>
<P>
Mamadou Bagayoko, head of the United Nations Children's Fund's
Basic Education unit, noted that the AIDS pandemic had contributed
a great deal to child labor, adding that in Africa AIDS had
effected children more than armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
Bagayoko said that Kenya had over 700,000 AIDS orphans, adding
that the number was expected to increase in the next millenium.
</P>
</TEXT>
