<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Writes to Rwanda Over Clashes in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Congo
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has sent a formal message to Rwanda stating Uganda's
stand on the probe report of the recent clashes between the two
countries' troops in Kisangani in the Democratic Republic of the
Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
He is expecting a formal response to the report from Kigali,
Saturday's New Vision quoted security sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
After the two countries' responses have been considered, the
two neighbors will agree on a position on the probe report, an
official attending a security meeting at State House was quoted
as saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Museveni has been angry with Rwandan Vice
 President and Minister of Defense Paul Kagame following the
release of the probe report on the August 14-17 clashes in which
both sides sustained heavy losses.
</P>
<P>
Museveni told the six-hour meeting Friday that he had advised
Kagame not to go public with the report compiled by Uganda Army
Commander Jeje Odongo and his Rwandan counterpart Kayumba
Nyamuswa.
</P>
<P>
Press reports here said that Kagame spilled the secrets of the
report while addressing the Rwandese National Assembly Thursday,
saying that Uganda was "100 percent responsible" for inciting the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's Army High Command has rejected the probe report,
citing it is biased and inconclusive and recommended setting up a
new inquiry team to expose the real causes of shoot-out in the
DRC.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that both parties have downplayed their losses
and accused each other of provoking the four-day exchange of fire
in the third largest city in the DRC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
