<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Seed Wang Nan Bumped out at China Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, China, September 18 (Xinhua) -- World number one women'
s paddler Wang Nan was bumped out of the '99 China Grand Prix
Table Tennis Championships final by Chinese-born German Qianghong
Gotsch here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Chinese attacking player, who crowned herself
as the new queen of the sport in last month's world champoinships
at Eindhoven, the Netherlands, fell to a defensively-minded Gotsch
15-21, 21-17, 13-21, 12-21 in one of the semi-finals on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Wang's perishment completed an anticlimax to the three-day ITTF
Pro-Tour event which closes this afternoon after top two men's
singles players, Liu Guoliang and Ma Lin, both from China, made a
premature exit one after another in Friday's competitions.
</P>
<P>
"Wang had a major injury problem with her left arm," said Lu
Yuansheng, head coach of the Chinese women's team. "And that cost
her, especially when tackling a top defensive player like He
Qianghong (as she was formerly known)."
</P>
<P>
It's the first time Wang, whose European shakehand style is
normally vunerable against defensive players, and the former
Chinese paddler faced off each other, Lu revealt.
</P>
<P>
Post-world championships fatigue also played a role in her
premature failure, Lu said.
</P>
<P>
"You'll find it hard to motivate yourself after a major triumph
in the world championships. You just can't work up yourself under
less pressure like competing such tournament," Lu said.
</P>
<P>
Wang threw away the first set in a blink before taking the
second 21-17, but Gotsch spiked up her defensive play with some
fast-attacking flavor in the following two sets, to which the
defending champion failed to respond.
</P>
<P>
As the game wore on, Wang apparently lost her fighting spirits
in a battle of patience, spurting out unforced errors and always
being the losing end of the lengthy rallies.
</P>
<P>
A gallant Gotsch, refusing to be intimidated by Wang's
trademark powerful forehand smashes and a full house of partisan
crowd, pumped her fists after finally bring down the world
champion to size.
</P>
<P>
The veteran player, ranked seventh in the ITTF world rankings,
will have to battle against another Chinese opposition in the
shape of Li Ju, who thrashed her teammate Li Nan 21-14, 21-17, 21-
16 in the other semi-final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
