<HEADLINE> Kenya's Motor Business Stagnant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Exhibitors at Kenya's 1999
Total Motor show complain that business was at its lowest due to
flooding of second- hand cars and the country's economic
depression.
</P>
<P>
Exhibitors at the show were eager to attract potential
customers to view their vehicles and other items on display,
however, the event was not as well-attended as they had hoped,
according Saturday's Daily Nation.
</P>
<P>
"It has been a bad season for the entire motor vehicle
industry," said a salesman for Toyota as the fair entered its
second day Friday.
</P>
<P>
Exhibitors also stressed on the ability of their vehicles
models to withstand the rough Kenyan roads.
</P>
<P>
"Our model is made just for the Kenyan conditions," said David
Dunahay, managing director of General Motors.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 companies are participating in the show. They
include motor vehicle companies, tyre companies and car accessory
dealers.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's economy has been in the doldrums in past few years. It
is predicted that economic growth for this year is less than 1.6
percent while the population growth in the east African country
is over three percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
