<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Genghis Khan's Descendant Lives As Common Citizen (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Editor's note: This year is the 50th anniversary of the
founding of the People's Republic of China. Xinhua News Agency is
releasing about 50 stories on Chinese men and women, young and old,
to illustrate the changes that have taken place in China over the
past half century. These people will describe their lives and how
they fit into the changes in the motherland. This is the 28th
story.
</P>
<P>
HOHHOT, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The sole-surviving 34th-
generation descendant of Genghis Khan just wants to be an ordinary
citizen and lead a quiet life.
</P>
<P>
Qi Zhongyi is the last Mongolian prince in the royal line that
started with Genghis Khan, who founded ancient Mongolia and whose
grandson Kublai Khan established the Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368).
When he is now compiling books on local history, Qi likes to grow
flowers, vegetables and fruit trees in his small courtyard of a
bungalow in the city of Dongsheng, in the southwest part of the
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
He resigned from the vice-chairmanship of north China's Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Regional Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
When he was just 16, Qi helped his grandfather in political
affairs, and he ascended the throne four months before New China
was founded on October 1, 1949.
</P>
<P>
"I was in great fear at that time for I didn't know what the
central government would do to a feudal prince," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Sack Corrupt Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Instant Dismissal awaits
corrupt civil servants, Kenya's Head of Civil Service Richard
Leaky has warned.
</P>
<P>
East African Standard newspaper Saturday quoted Leakey as
saying that corruption was a cancer that must be eliminated at all
costs and the vice had pushed the country into doldrums.
</P>
<P>
Civil service cutback will be implemented within the next three
months and steps are being taken to ensure staff are disciplined
and accountable to the public, Leakey said at an anti-corruption
workshop.
</P>
<P>
Corruption has undermined efficiency and ruined Kenya's
relationship with the outside world especially the donor
community, he said.
</P>
<P>
He decried the level of corruption in Kenya by narrating how a
resident in central Kenya's Rift Valley Province had to labor in
order to secure a birth certificate for his new-born child.
</P>
<P>
Richard Leaky was appointed to head of civil service in July as
part of economic recovery plan of Kenyan President Daniel Arap
Moi.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's economy has been in decline since the International
Monetary Fund suspended a 205 million U.S. dollars loan to Kenya
in protest at corruption in the east African country in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Genghis Khan's Descendant Lives as Common Citizen (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He turned his allegiance to the Chinese Communist Party in
August 1949, and thought that he would be permitted to earn a
living as a teacher. To his surprise, he was elected a banner head
in March 1950.
</P>
<P>
"I became a prince again. However, this time it was quite
different from before. I had no servants and what I needed to do
then was to serve the residents in my banner," said he.
</P>
<P>
He then was promoted to vice chairman of the Ih Ju League in
southwest Inner Mongolia in July 1956, a position he had held
until the chaotic Cultural Revolution started in 1966.
</P>
<P>
He spent a lot of time studying the daily lives of the
residents during his tenure as vice chairman of the Ih Ju League.
And in 1979, he was appointed vice chairman of the Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Regional Committee of the CPPCC.
</P>
<P>
"Great changes have taken place in my country in the past fifty
years. Now, I can either take cars or airplanes. The best
transportation for me when I was a prince was just a horse," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, he has compiled 30 books on the local history based
on what he has learned at work and his own observations.
</P>
<P>
"What I have experienced convinced me that it is the wise
policies of the Central Government on ethnic minorities, the
regional autonomy policy in particular, that have led to political
stability and harmony among the ethnic groups, as it has taken
into consideration every ethnic group's interests," he said.
</P>
<P>
He is now working on his autobiography called "the Last Prince
in China," which compares his experiences as a prince and a
government official in New China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
