<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul Hails U.S. Partial Lifting of Economic Sanctions Against DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 18 (Xinhua) -- South Korea on Saturday
welcomed the United States' partial lifting of its economic
sanctions against the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
In a statement, South Korean Foreign Ministry said the partial
lifting of sanctions is in line with the comprehensive engagement
policy pursued by the Kim Dae-jung government and has fostered an
atmosphere favorable to the policy.
</P>
<P>
It said Seoul will continue the engagement policy and urged the
DPRK to respond to the U.S. measure to clear suspicions over the
DPRK missile development program.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton has announced to ease trade and
economic sanctions against Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
The measure, the first since the end of the Korean War in 1953,
will allow the export of U.S. consumer goods to the DPRK and will
permit the import of the DPRK's commodities.
</P>
<P>
However, Washington said it will reimpose the sanctions if
Pyongyang resumes testing missiles of any kind as both sides move
towards normal relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
