<HEADLINE> Xinhua Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, September 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Statistics Canada reported Friday that the annual
inflation rate in August rose to 2.1 percent, at its highest level
since February.
</P>
<P>
The annual inflation rate was respectively registered at 1.8
percent in July and 1.6 percent in June. (Canada-Inflation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Commerce Department said Friday that new
construction of houses and apartments in the country increased 0.4
percent in August despite rising mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
U.S. builders started new homes at a seasonally adjusted rate
of 1.68 million units last month, the department reported.
</P>
<P>
The report said that housing climbed 3.9 percent in July,
recovering from a slide of 3.7 percent in June. Both monthly
revised estimates were smaller than first reported. (US-Housing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB) will provide
Cambodia with a loan of 20 million U.S. dollars under an agreement
signed here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to support the country's water supply and
sewage treatment projects.
</P>
<P>
With the new loan, the ADB has offered a total of 88 million U.
S. dollars of loans to Cambodia so far this year, compared with 40
million U.S. dollars in 1998. (Cambodia-ADB-Loan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA -- Ethiopia, one of the poorest countries in the
world, has owed 10 billion U.S. dollars foreign debt, according to
the latest issue of Ethiopian weekly Press Digest.
</P>
<P>
On the list of African debtor countries, Ethiopia stands fifth.
The total debts of African countries is 350 billion U.S. dollars,
the weekly quoted New Africa Magazine as saying. (Ethiopia-Debt)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Gulf producers of glass and glass products should
merge operations to make their products more competitive, a Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) industrial thinktank has suggested.
</P>
<P>
"Mergers have become an important means for sectoral
restructuring in all regions of the world. Glass manufactures,
particularly glass bottle producers, in the GCC should consider
this option seriously for better competitiveness of their products
and establishments," said the latest monthly bulletin of the Doha-
based Gulf Organization for Industrial Consulting GOIC), which was
published on Friday. (UAE-Glass-Merger) 
</P>
</TEXT>
