<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bad Time for Czech-Slovak Ties Is Over, Presidents Say </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Slovakian President Rudolf
Schuster and his visiting Czech counterpart Vaclav Havel said at a
joint press conference on Friday that the cold period between the
two countries has come to an end and a new era of cooperation has
begun.
</P>
<P>
They said there are no major political or ethnic problems
remaining unsolved.
</P>
<P>
Czech President Havel began his first ever, two-day state visit
to Slovakia on Friday and has held talks with the Slovakian
president in Bratislava, capital of Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents revealed that the two countries have largely
reached agreement on property division, with only a few technical
problems requiring further discussions.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is expected to be signed by the prime ministers
of the two countries within this year, according to them.
</P>
<P>
The Czech leader also reaffirmed his commitment to fully
supporting Slovakia's bid for the membership of NATO and the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents pledged that their two countries would
support each other in their efforts for joining Europe's political
and economic structures.
</P>
<P>
During their talks held earlier in the day, the two presidents
agreed that the two countries would enhance bilateral ties and
assist each other in Europe's integration process and expand
cooperation on regional and international matters.
</P>
<P>
Havel has also met with Chairman of the Slovak National Council
Jozef Migas and Prime Minister Mikulas Dzurinda to exchange views
on further development of political and economical ties between
their two nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
