<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Importers Suffer Big Blow From Yen's Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Thai importers are suffering
a double blow from the yen's rapid rise and the baht's weakness
against the greenback, The Nation reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted the latest report of the Thai Farmers
Research Center that imports will become more expensive and
inflation was likely to rise significantly, given that Japan is
the largest source of Thai imports with a yearly average of over
10 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Thailand mainly imports capital items, semi-finished goods and
raw materials, such as machinery and equipment, currency and
steel, chemical products and automobiles from Japan.
</P>
<P>
The center said the higher yen value will result in higher
import costs. Given the rising price of oil, inflation will soon
go up very fast.
</P>
<P>
The Thai currency's weakness will also give importers a harder
time as the price of their imported goods will jump in line with
the falling baht value.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, Thai exporters are reaping a windfall from the
higher yen value, which jumped to 103.55 yen against the U.S.
dollar on September 15, giving exporters greater competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Thai products will become much cheaper in yen terms, which will
bolster the prospects for the country's overall export
performance.
</P>
<P>
The center also said yen's rise will lead to an ever-larger
Thai trade deficit with Japan. The gap gets wider each year and
tends to rise in line with a stronger yen.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the center predicted that external debts of
Thailand would rise dramatically. Yen-denominated loans now
account for over 33 percent of all external debts in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the research house said that the stronger yen would
lead to a higher capital inflow from Japan and that more Japanese
investors were likely to relocate to other Asian economies,
including Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
