<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Experts oppose Idea of Community Clinics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September18 -- The government plans to set up 13,500
community clinics by 2003 for delivery of Essential Service
Package (ESP), but many experts oppose the idea.
</P>
<P>
ESP is a major component of the fifth five-year health sector
reform program known as Health and Population Sector Program
(HPSP).
</P>
<P>
The concept of Community Clinic has bee adopted in the HPSP to
ensure health and family planning services at grassroots level and
easy access to healthcare services. One clinic costing about Taka
200,000 ( around 4000 U.S. Dollars) would be set up for every 6000
rural people.
</P>
<P>
However, setting up of community clinics to provide healthcare
is opposed by many experts, according to a report published by the
local newspaper " The Daily Star" on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Utilization of healthcare facility at present is less than 40
percent which is considered "Quite poor", they mentioned.
</P>
<P>
The government over the years established some health
complexes, health sub-centers at union level and subsequently set
up more and more health centers. but unfortunately, it proved to
be of little help for the targeted population, they said, adding
the existing healthcare facilities must be made more efficient
before undertaking any new venture for healthcare facility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
