<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> KLA to Complete Disarmament Process: KFOR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 17 (Xinhua) -- NATO peacekeepers in Kosovo
(KFOR) said Friday that the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) will
complete its disarmament process by the midnight of Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Kosovo's capital of Pristina, the KFOR
said that the KLA has so far surrendered more than 10,000 pieces
of weapons, and those they are keeping to protect their barracks
will be turned to the peacekeepers on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
After Saturday, the KLA members could wear their uniforms only
in the areas controlled by the KFOR. A "Kosovo Corps" consisting
of 5,000 people will be established after the KLA is disarmed,
said the statement.
</P>
<P>
However, the Yugoslav press said that the United Nations has
never authorized the international peacekeepers in Kosovo to set
up such a corps, and that what they are intending to do is to
legalize the status of the ethnic Albanian rebels.
</P>
<P>
Under Resolution 1244 of the UN, Saturday is the deadline for
the KLA's disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia, which insists that the KLA be completely disarmed
and disbanded, has said the disarmament of the Kosovo Liberation
Army (KLA) was a farce because the rebel group was hiding its best
weapons in Albania, Macedonia and secret storage spots inside
Kosovo, the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Vladislav Jovanovic, charge d'affaires of
the Yugoslav Mission to the United Nations, was speaking at a
press conference here.
</P>
<P>
"They surrender what is old-fashioned, vintage and not of much
importance," he said. "But what is really modern and efficient
they conceal."
</P>
<P>
The senior Yugoslav diplomat accused NATO and the United
Nations of backing the KLA and its goal of an independent Kosovo,
and of encouraging KLA fighters to join the police, the civilian
administration of towns and villages, and a new national guard.
</P>
<P>
This has undermined a United Nations resolution and violated
the sovereignty and territorial integrity of Yugoslavia, he said.
</P>
<P>
Security Council Resolution 1244, adopted on June 10, demands
that every State Member and the world body fully respect the
sovereignty and territorial integrity of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Russia insists on the complete disbanding and demilitarization
of the rebel army and sees the new force as part of international
attempts to weaken the hold on the province of its traditional
ally, Serbia, a Yugoslav republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
