<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Floyd Takes Last Bite in Eastern Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Hurricane Floyd took one last
bite in eastern Canada, leaving tens of thousands of people
without power Friday.
</P>
<P>
Up to 40,000 people in Quebec are rendered out of power in
addition to another 1,300 people plunged into blackout in the
Atlantic provinces of New Brunswick and Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
The CTV reported damage caused by the downgrading Floyd, which
was still powerful enough to knock down trees, power lines and
houses in Halifax, Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
The television also reported minor injuries caused by traffic
accidents in the storm, which brought 13 centimeters of rain to
some areas, with strong winds moving at 104 kilometers an hour at
its worst.
</P>
<P>
Maritime Canada braced for the advent of the storm as early as
Wednesday, when schools were closed in the southern part of Nova
Scotia and water surfers were warned to stay away from the beach,
where waves were witnessed surging five to seven meters high ahead
of the storm.
</P>
<P>
Hurricane Floyd has caused at least 19 deaths and millions of
dollars in damage since it first pounded the Bahamas Tuesday with
winds blowing at 250 kilometers an hour.
</P>
<P>
Over 3 million Americans were reported fleeing their homes when
the storm landed late Tuesday in Florida and then moved across
Georgia, Carolinas, Virginia, Maryland, New Jersey, New York and
Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
