<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hoya, Trinidad to Square off in Welterweight Blockbuster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The biggest non-
heavyweight fight in more than a decade takes place Saturday night
in Las Vegas when Oscar de la Hoya, the unbeaten WBC champion,
squares off with Felix Trinidad, the undefeated IBF titleholder.
</P>
<P>
De la Hoya, "the Golden Boy" (31-0, 25 KOs), is the sport's
most marketable commodity and the linchpin of HBO's boxing empire.
He has crossover appeal and, at 26, is still in his prime.
</P>
<P>
"I want to knock him out for my fans," de la Hoya said. "I
know I can do it. I'm very prepared for this fight. May the best
man win."
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old Trinidad (35-0, 30 KOs), a Puerto Rican who
speaks little English, has been protected from the media by his
father and trainer, Felix Sr., who also was a boxer. Trinidad's
allure is stunning knockout power that is offset by a suspect chin.
</P>
<P>
"I will knock de la Hoya out," Trinidad said through an
interpreter. "That's the only way I can win and I know he can't
handle my power. Remember, you heard it here first."
</P>
<P>
The fight has drawn incredible interest from fight fans who see
the bout as possibly the first in a classic series. Most compare
the matchup to the first Sugar Ray Leonard-Thomas Hearns bout in
1981.
</P>
<P>
"He is like Tommy Hearns in this match, bigger, a stronger
puncher with great power in both hands," de la Hoya said. "I'm
kind of like Sugar Ray, because I can box and punch. Like Hearns
and Leonard, our styles are different, and that will make for a
very exciting match."
</P>
<P>
Oddsmakers agree on the competitiveness of the fight, with de
la Hoya a slight 6-5 favorite. De la Hoya also has the edge in
purse, receiving at least 15 million U.S. dollars while Trinidad
gets $10 million.
</P>
<P>
The bout is expected to be the biggest grossing non-heavyweight
fight of all time and among the top five events in pay-per-view
history. When de la Hoya fought Pernell Whitaker in April 1997,
the bout recorded 800,000 buys. At 49.95 U.S. dollars, this fight
should generate more than 40 million U.S. dollars in PPV revenue.
</P>
<P>
"I am ready to get in the ring and show that there can only be
one undefeated champion, and it's going to be me," de la Hoya said.
</P>
<P>
"I know he will get the majority of the fans that night,"
Trinidad added. "It doesn't matter. It will be just him and me in
the ring."
</P>
<P>
De la Hoya is 20-0 in title fights while Trinidad has made 14
successful defense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
