<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Board Approves Rules Changes Geared Toward Offense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The NBA went back to the
future on Saturday as its Board of Governors approved rules
changes that hopefully will reduce rough play and improve
offensive flow, an element that has eroded during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The rules modifications were recommended in June by a special
committee and were used during summer league games. They will be
implemented in the 1999-2000 season.
</P>
<P>
"These rules will help us fine-tune and improve the look and
flow of our game," NBA senior vice president of basketball
operations Rod Thorn said. "We realize there will probably be a
transitional period for everyone involved to get used to the
changes, but we believe that they will improve the game."
</P>
<P>
Scoring dropped for the 10th straight year last season to 91.6
points per game, four points lower than the 1997-98 season and the
lowest averages since the inception of the shot clock in 1954.
The NBA Finals between the San Antonio Spurs and New York Knicks
produced the two lowest five-game point totals in history.
</P>
<P>
The two biggest changes involved a reduction in hand-checking
and the 24-second clock, which will not be reset or reset to just
14 seconds after certain violations.
</P>
<P>
A defender no longer will be allowed to make contact with his
hands or forearms on an offensive player above the foul line
extended. Quick players such as Philadelphia 76ers guard Allen
Iverson were being slowed by physical play ranging from a hand on
the hip to being shoved off course.
</P>
<P>
On non-shooting fouls, illegal defense warnings and kicked or
punched balls, the shot clock will not be reset if already above
14 seconds and will be reset to 14 seconds if below 14 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The belief is that extra possessions will be generated by these
new guidelines. Previously, the shot clock always was reset to 24
seconds in those situations.
</P>
<P>
The board also approved a five-second rule which forces a
player to shoot, pass or pick up his dribble if he begins
dribbling with his back toward the basket below the foul line
extended.
</P>
<P>
This rule would prevent players such as Houton Rockets forward
Charles Barkley and Indiana Pacers guard Mark Jackson from backing
in opponents and bringing team play to a grinding halt.
</P>
<P>
Finally, defenders will be allowed to leave the men and chase
the ball or pressure another offensive player as long as they are
on the strong side of the court.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member committee was made up of players, coaches,
general managers and owners. NBA commissioner David Stern and
deputy commissioner Russ Granik sat in on the meetings and
supervisor of officials Ed Rush made a video presentation that
showed the increase in physical play and the incremental
deterioration of offensive flow.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, the league scoring average was 109 points per game.
It dipped below 100 points per game in the 1995-96 season and only
one team -- the Sacramento Kings -- averaged triple figures last
season.
</P>
<P>
The new rules should lead to an increase in fouls as players
get acclimated. In June, Thorn maintained the NBA referees would
call games as they were instructed -- a serious bone of contention
in baseball this season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. "Dream Team" to Face Russia for Fed Cup Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A formidable United States
team featuring four of the top five players in the world will be a
heavy favorite against Russia when the two nations meet for the
Federation Cup title, beginning Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The best-of-five series will take place at Stanford University
on the hardcourt surface in California as the U.S. looks to extend
its own record of 15 Fed Cup titles.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. squad will be comprised of reigning U.S. Open champion
Serena Williams, Wimbledon champion Lindsay Davenport, Serena's
older sister and world No. 3 Venus and world No. 5 Monica Seles.
</P>
<P>
Serena Williams beat Seles in the U.S. Open quarter-finals and
Davenport in the semi-finals before upsetting top-ranked Martina
Hingis of Switzerland to win her first Grand Slam singles title.
The 17-year-old moved up to a career-high No. 4 in the WTA Tour
rankings with her performance in New York.
</P>
<P>
Substituting for an injured Seles in the Fed Cup semi-finals
against Italy, Serena provided the clinching win in the 4-1 series
victory. Making their Fed Cup debut, the Williams sisters
combined for all four victories.
</P>
<P>
Davenport, 23, came up short in her bid to defend her U.S. Open
title, but remained at No. 2 in the world.
</P>
<P>
The 19-year-old Venus Williams lost to Hingis in the U.S. Open
semi-finals, but she teamed with Serena to win the doubles title
and most likely will be the doubles tandem this weekend.
</P>
<P>
A nine-time Grand Slam champion, Seles is the oldest player on
the team at 25. She owns a 11-1 record in Fed Cup competition.
</P>
<P>
Led by Elena Likhovtseva and Tatiana Panova, Russia defeated
Slovakia 3-2 in the semifinals after upsetting a strong French
team in the opening round. Likhovtseva and Panova will be joined
by Elena Dementieva and Elena Makarova for the final.
</P>
<P>
Russia has never won a Fed Cup title, but reached the final in
1988 and 1990. This will be the fourth meeting between the two
nations, and the United States has won all three previous meetings.
</P>
</TEXT>
