<HEADLINE> Indonesian Sports Minister Against Sending Athletes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Minister of Sports
and Youth Affairs Agung Laksono said he would be against sending a
sporting delegation to 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney, "if Australia
carries on with its unfriendly attitude towards Indonesia".
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the political ties between Indonesia and
Australia were experiencing the biggest decline due to the
unfriendly statements by Australian officials over the East Timor
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"If the tension goes from bad to worse, what do we send
athletes to Australia for? Athletes are the nation's ambassadors.
What do we send the ambassadors for, to a country which looks
arrogant and less amicable," he was quoted by The Indonesian
Observer Saturday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government on Thursday canceled a security pact
with Australia, denouncing Australia's attitude and actions on the
East Timor issue.
</P>
<P>
Anti-Australia sentiment has grown stronger all over Indonesia
with demonstrators taking to the streets everyday slamming
Australia.
</P>
<P>
Agung said: "Given the prevalent attitude of Australia, the
Indonesian government must heed the people's sentiments. If the
ties worsen and if Australia is persistent in its arrogant
attitude and remains repugnant to us. Well, what's the use of
participating in the Olympics?"
</P>
<P>
However, he said that preparations, including the campaign to
win places at Sydney Olympics through qualifications, were and
would be going ahead as planned.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has been assured of participation in Sydney in
athletics, badminton, archery, swimming, surfing and taekwondo,
whilst weightlifting, boxing and tennis are the only other three
disciplines in which Indonesian athletes have better prospects for
qualifying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
