<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Laos Promotes Rice Production, Multilateral Trade to Save Crisis-Hit Economy: Lao FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Laos has taken various
measures to alleviate the impact of the financial crisis on the
already weak economy, Lao Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign
Minister Somsawat Lengsavad told Xinhua in an interview in the Lao
capital of Vientiane recently.
</P>
<P>
When introducing the current economic situation of one of the
least developed countries in the world, the minister said that the
financial crisis took a heavy toll of the Lao economy.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that his country's economy has shown signs of
serious problems even before the crisis, which broke out in
mid-1997 from its southern neighbor Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"The domestic production could not meet the demand of the
people, while the infrastructure of the country is lagging far
behind due to years of war," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He particularly mentioned the infrastructure construction of
the country, saying that it could not be sustained due to the
budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
The country's revenue stands at more than 200 million U.S.
dollars, while the deficit is at 100 million dollars, accounting
for nearly 50 percent of the budget.
</P>
<P>
The country's infrastructure has been mainly dependent on
foreign aid, he said.
</P>
<P>
As for Laos' foreign trade, Somsawat said that too much
imports, especially imports from Thailand, is the major problem
his country, the only landlocked state in southeast Asia, is
facing.
</P>
<P>
In Vientiane, which borders Thailand by the Mekong river, about
70 percent of the goods sold in local stores are from the opposite
side of the river.
</P>
<P>
Some 80 percent of Laos' external trade are conducted with
Thailand, which made the Lao economy vulnerable to any turmoil in
Thailand, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the country was plunged into a deeper mire than
its neighbor after the latter devalued its currency, the baht, in
July 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Lao currency, the kip, has been depreciated to 9,400-9,700
kips against the U.S. dollar now from 920 kips to the greenback in
July 1997.
</P>
<P>
The fluctuation of the kip further dampened the economic
situation as foreign investors shunned the country, the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
To alleviate the impact of the crisis, the Lao government has
taken a series of measures, among which the increase of rice
production has been greatly highlighted.
</P>
<P>
The country has been focusing on the expansion of the planting
of double-harvest rice to feed its people, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, the country had only 25,000 hectares of such rice,
while in 1997-1998 season, the area for the rice had increased by
28,000 hectares to 53,000 hectares, and in 1998-1999 season, the
area increased to 87,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that in the upcoming 1999-2000 season,
double-harvest rice will be planted in at least 100,000 hectares
of land in Laos.
</P>
<P>
"When there is no problem feeding the people, there will be no
need to import so many goods," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Laos is also trying to avoid being too dependent on Thailand in
trade by promoting trade with other neighbors like Vietnam and
China.
</P>
<P>
As part of the efforts to lure foreign investment, the country
worked out a foreign investment management act, which was amended
in 1997 and passed by the parliament later.
</P>
<P>
The act has helped to create a friendly investment environment.
As a result, more than 30 countries and regions have come to Laos
for investment with contract amount totaling six billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The financial crisis has given Laos a lesson, making the
country realize the importance of being independent," the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
The country now plans to make full use of its own resources,
trade with more countries and attract more foreign investment so
as to bring the country out of the crisis, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
