<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Massive Electricity Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has launched a
9.665 billion rupees (138.2 million U.S. dollars) program with
foreign loans to augment its electricity transmission system in a
bid to meet the increasing power demand, officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The program is assisted by Credit Institute of Restoration and
Reconstruction (KFW) of Germany, the World Bank, the Overseas
Economic Cooperation Fund (OECF) of Japan, the Norwegian
government and the Asian Development Bank (ADB) in the form of
soft loans, said a spokesman for the Ministry of Power.
</P>
<P>
He said the KFW would provide 765 million rupees (11 million
dollars) to establish a new grid substation at Kelaniya and
rehabilitate another at Ratmalana, both in Colombo's suburbs.
</P>
<P>
The replacing of the grid substation at Kolonnawa with a new
one and the upgrading of the Pannipitiya grid substation, funded
by the World Bank with 2.7 billion rupees (38.6 million dollars),
will remedy the shortcomings in the supply of electricity in the
Colombo area by the year 2002, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The installation of the new grid substations in Ratnapura and
Athurugiriya in central Sri Lanka at a cost of 3.4 billion rupees
(48.6 million dollars) assisted by the OECF of Japan will also
improve the electricity transmission system covered by them.
</P>
<P>
The proposed new grid substation in northern Vavuniya at a cost
of 300 million rupees (4.3 million dollars) with Norwegian
assistance will also enable the government to restore the power
supply to the Northern province in the first quarter of the year
2001.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is also working on a project to install 12 grid
substations at a cost of 2.5 billion rupees (35.7 million dollars)
with ADB assistance, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
About 55 percent of 18.5 million Sri Lankans have access to
electricity. The government has decided to observe 1999-2009 as a
decade of power development in a move to provide every household
with electricity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts and Figures on Lives of Chinese People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Editor's note: The People's Republic of China celebrates its
50th founding anniversary this year and Xinhua will release 10
stories on key facts and figures on the nation's economic and
social developments over the last half century. This is the fourth
in the series.
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The lives of the Chinese
people have improved tremendously since the founding of the People
's Republic of China in 1949, especially since 1978, when the
country started its reform and opening policy. This is indicated
by the following facts and figures:
</P>
<P>
The average disposable income for China's urban residents was 5,
425 yuan in 1998, up 220 percent up from the 1978 level in real
terms.
</P>
<P>
From 1949 to 1998, annual cash income for China's rural
residents rose from 44 to 2,162 yuan, up 48-fold.
</P>
<P>
The actual spending of each Chinese was 2,973 yuan in 1998,
compared to 80 yuan in 1952.
</P>
<P>
China's private saving deposits reached 5,340.7 billion yuan in
1998, up by 6,200 times over that of 1952, and 254 times over 1978.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, food accounted for 45 percent of the total spending of
China's urban residents, and 53 percent of that of rural residents.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1998, 68 percent of China's urban families lived
in flats, 74 percent of them had bathrooms or toilets in their own
houses, and 72 percent cooked with gas or liquefied petroleum gas.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1998, the average housing space for China's rural
families was 24 square meters.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1998, every 100 Chinese rural families had 137
bicycles, 96 television sets, 32 cassette recorders, 112 electric
fans, 23 washing machines and nine refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
Also at the end of 1998, every 100 Chinese urban families owned
105 television sets, 76 refrigerators, 91 washing machines, 36
cameras, 20 air conditioners, four personal computers, 64 fixed
telephones, three mobile phones, and 0.3 autos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Stocks Slightly Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican Stock
Exchange on Friday closed down with benchmark IPC index falling 18.
56 points or 0.37 percent, at 4,951.68 points.
</P>
<P>
Brokers exchanged 33.263 million shares worth 115.679 million U.
S. dollars against 49.314 million shares for an amount of some 115.
639 million dollars on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Stock exchanges in Mexico had no trading on Thursday, Mexico's
Independent Day.
</P>
<P>
The local currency, peso, maintained unchanged at 9.50 to on
dollar for sale and 9.15 for purchase in the Bank of Mexico.
</P>
