<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wang Junxia's Run in 1993 Worlds "Greatest Ever" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The startling race of Chinese
woman long-distance runner Wang Junxia at the fourth world
championships in 1993 is rated as the greatest ever on the world
record books.
</P>
<P>
British statistician Howard Grubb, from Reading University,
compiled the 200 all-time bests in each track event from 100
meters up to marathons. He then compared the speeds of the
athletes at each distance and saw a smooth trend for both men and
women.
</P>
<P>
He identified the very best performances by spotting which
world records stuck out above the general trend.
</P>
<P>
By comparison, Grubb concluded that Wang's 10,000m run in
Stuttgart, Germany six years ago was the best world mark.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistician, the most remarkable performances
are as follows (compared to an average of 100%):
</P>
<P>
1. Wang Junxia -- 10,000m -- September 1993 -- 102%
</P>
<P>
2. Wang Junxia -- 3,000m -- September 1993 -- 101.5%
</P>
<P>
3. Haile Gebrselassie -- 10,000m -- June 1998 -- 101.1%
</P>
<P>
4. Michael Johnson -- 200m -- August 1996 -- 100.9%
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the analysis, the women's 5,000m record
should be the most vulnerable to attack, rating just 98.9% whilst
the men's event lying furthest below average is the 100m.
</P>
<P>
Maurice Green, the world's fastest man at 9.79 seconds over the
distance, should be aiming for 9.71 seconds to reach Grubb's
predicted world record.
</P>
<P>
However, Grubb acknowledges that some will disagree with his
approach. "The particular conditions of a race, if the weather
was hot or cold, if a pacemaker was used, could have an effect,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
