<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Rebels Want Resumption of Dialog with Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's National
Liberation Army (ELN), the second largest rebel group in the
country, announced Friday that it would like to resume direct
peace talks with the government.
</P>
<P>
This message came from Thursday's meeting between an ELN leader
and business leaders in Caracas, which was aimed at breathing life
into stalled peace talks between the guerrilla group and the
Colombian government.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, initiated by Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez and
authorized by the Colombian government, was attended by business
leaders, Colombian Attorney General Jaime Bernal Cuellar and ELN
Central Committee delegate Pablo Beltran.
</P>
<P>
One of the business leaders, Sabas Pretelt, said that the peace
talks between the ELN and the government could be resumed even
before the release of some 56 hostages the ELN took during three
mass kidnappings in the first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The ELN will hope to seek an agreement with the government on
creating a buffer zone, similar to the one granted to the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC), the largest
guerrilla group in the country, Pretelt said.
</P>
<P>
Contacts between the government and the ELN broke off after the
rebel group staged two mass kidnappings involving a commercial
airliner and a church congregation in April and May.
</P>
<P>
The death toll of Colombia's civil war has exceeded 35,000 in
the last decade, as guerrillas, right-wing death squads and the U.
S.-trained army battle for control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
