<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Delays Multinational Force Arrival in Dili: Indonesian Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has
delayed the arrival of an advance team of the International Force
in East Timor (Interfet) in Dili, capital of East Timor, according
to the Indonesian Military (TNI).
</P>
<P>
"The transfer of mandate to restore peace and order in East
Timor from TNI to the multinational force remains hanging in the
balance. I've received a call from Cilangkap (TNI Headquarters)
that the advance team will not come by Saturday or early next
week," Maj. Gen. Kiki Syahnakri, head of the Restoration Operation
Command in East Timor, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said the fact that both TNI and the United Nations had yet
to agree on the cooperation scheme might have caused the delay.
</P>
<P>
He added that he also received a call from TNI Headquarters
that Interfet Commander Maj. Gen. Peter Cosgrove would not come to
Dili on Saturday as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Cosgrove was scheduled to lead a 250-member advanced team,
which would include 65 British Gurkhas, to Dili on Saturday. The
first 2,000 of some 8,000 international soldiers were expected to
follow the advance team in a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
"Ideally, the transfer of military command should take place a
week after the main body of the U.N. multinational force sets foot
in East Timor," Kiki was quoted by The Jakarta Post Saturday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Despite the delay, the withdrawal of TNI troops continued on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
TNI said in a statement on Friday that some 8,000 troops in
East Timor have left or were on their way out of the territory and
entering the border town of Atambua in the western half of Timor
island.
</P>
<P>
As of Thursday, there were one Marine unit and 12 Army
battalions in East Timor, as well as 8,000 police and 5,000
members of the local military command.
</P>
<P>
Kiki said his troops blocked off all access to Dili to prevent
pro-Jakarta militias from attacking the multinational force.
</P>
<P>
"We have set up a post in Tasitolu, west of Dili, where we
conduct a weapon search on everybody entering the capital," Kiki
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
