<HEADLINE> China to Regulate Foreign-Involved Surveying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- China will reinforce
management of foreign-involved surveying and mapping activities,
today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The paper cited Huang Yunkang, deputy director of the State
Bureau of Surveying and Mapping, as saying that according to
Chinese laws any foreigners who wants to conduct surveying and
mapping activities within China's borders and territorial waters
must report to the Chinese authorities.
</P>
<P>
The paper explains that in recent years some foreigners have
surveyed parts of the country without first reporting to the
Chinese authorities.
</P>
<P>
In a case, a foreign exploration team carried out surveying and
mapping of regions along the Great Wall without registering with
the State surveying and mapping administration department, the
paper reveals.
</P>
<P>
According to Huang, the activity of surveying and mapping is a
matter of national sovereignty and security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
