<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU: Disagreements With Mexico Unresolved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 17 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU)
ambassador to Mexico Manuel Lopez Blanco said Friday that customs
tariff disagreements have hampered negotiations of a free trade
agreement (FTA) between the European bloc and this Latin American
country.
</P>
<P>
The EU "does not understand" why Mexico demands more
flexibility in the rules of origin for the automobile and
electronics sectors than what it obtained in the North American
Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) with the United States and Canada,
Lopez Blanco said.
</P>
<P>
"We (the EU and Mexico) are not near an agreement. One or more
rounds of talks are necessary because there are important matters
that require deeper studies," said Lopez Blanco.
</P>
<P>
According to Lopez Blanco, there are disagreements in some 200
custom tariffs in the chapter of rules of origin.
</P>
<P>
Mexico demands that automobile and electronics exports with 40
percent of national parts from Mexico be granted a preferential
treatment in the European market. The EU rejected it on the ground
that this proposal would benefit foreign producers to export their
products to Europe.
</P>
<P>
The EU representative said that Mexico's positions on both
issues would inhibit investment in the Latin American country,
which risks to become only a processor of intermediate goods.
</P>
<P>
The EU asks Mexico to reduce tariffs to 10 percent or lower by
the year 2005, and "we are waiting for an interesting answer from
Mexico" in the next round of talks scheduled for September 27,
said the diplomat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
