<HEADLINE> Floyd Hurricane Death Toll Rises to 29 in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- At least 29 people were
killed in the Unite States as Hurricane Floyd swept up the eastern
seaboard in the past few days with record rains that flooded
scores of towns and forced the evacuation of three million people
from communities, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, thousands of homes and businesses were damaged, and
over one million households were without power in Virginia,
Maryland, Delaware, Pennsylvania, New Jersey and Connecticut
States. Utility companies warned that many would be without
electricity into the weekend.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, emergency workers in boats and Marines in
helicopters swarmed into North Carolina State's coastal plain to
rescue over 1,000 people from roofs and trees after the torrential
rains of Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
In southeastern Pennsylvania State, more than 4,000 people were
homeless Friday after torrential rains sent rivers over their
banks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton Friday declared an emergency in New
Jersey because of Hurricane Floyd, opening the way for the state
to apply for federal money to help with cleanup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
