<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Production of Pearls and Gems Drops in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The production of precious
minerals in Myanmar dropped in 1998-99 fiscal year, which ended on
March 31, compared with the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures of the country's Central Statistical
Organization, in the 1998-99, Myanmar produced 1.256 million
kilograms of jade, 5.588 million carats of rubies, 2.4 million
carats of sapphire, 981,297 carats of spinel and 12.59 kilograms
of pearls.
</P>
<P>
The production of these precious items respectively dropped by
percentage of 41.68, 24.29, 60.17, 5.49 and 5.24 as compared with
the 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar holds gems emporiums annually, putting on sale the
country's locally-produced gems, jade, pearl and jewelry through
the tender system or competitive bidding.
</P>
<P>
Such sale of Myanmar's precious stones has started since 1964
and the promotion of sale has also been strived by adding mid-year
gems emporiums every year since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The country earned a total of 271.3 million U.S. dollars from
the past 36 annual and seven mid-year gems emporiums which
attracted annually hundreds of gems merchants from over a dozen
countries and regions, mostly from China's Hong Kong, Thailand,
Japan and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, a well-known producer of jade, ruby and sapphire in
the world, is striving to create a systematic gem market in line
with its market-oriented economic system introduced in late 1988.
</P>
<P>
In addition to permitting the local private sector to mine and
process gems in the country, the government has also set up joint
ventures with companies from Thailand, Malaysia and Israel to
carry out gems extraction and processing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
