<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, September 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Yugoslavia has said the disarmament of the
Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) was a farce because the rebel group
was hiding its best weapons in Albania, Macedonia and secret
storage spots inside Kosovo, the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Vladislav Jovanovic, charge d'affaires of
the Yugoslav Mission to the United Nations, was speaking at a
press conference here. "They surrender what is old-fashioned,
vintage and not of much importance," he said. "But what is really
modern and efficient they conceal." The senior Yugoslav diplomat
also accused NATO and the United Nations of backing the KLA and
its goal of an independent Kosovo, and of encouraging KLA fighters
to join the police, the civilian administration of towns and
villages, and a new national guard. (UN-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus Defense Minister Socrates Hasikos left here
Friday for an official visit to Greece for talks with his Greek
counterpart Akis Tsohatzopoulos.
</P>
<P>
Hasikos said before departure that the two sides will discuss
bilateral cooperation in defense and will review a joint defense
pact signed in November 1993. Under the pact, Greece will provide
air, sea and land coverage to Cyprus in case of a new Turkish
offensive against the island. (Cyprus-Greece-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton has decided to ease
sanctions against the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK),
allowing more trade between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The measure, the first since the end of the Korean War in 1953,
will allow most consumer goods to be available for export to the
DPRK and will allow the import of DPRK goods into the United
States, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Friday.
Restrictions on transportation, banking and personnel movements
between the U.S. and the DPRK will also be relaxed, according to
the spokesman. (US-DPRK-Sanctions)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Chairman of NATO's Military Committee, Admiral
Guido Venturoni, said here Friday that the rebel Kosovo Liberation
Army (KLA) would partly become a police force in the future.
</P>
<P>
The new committee chief, who took office in May, said that the
ethnic Albanian rebel group will be disbanded and transformed into
civilian societies as the deadline falls Sunday. He said the KLA
men will be helped to find jobs and part of them will become
policemen in the province protected by the international forces.
The KLA hopes to transform about half of its 10,000 men into a
civilian defense corps. Rebel officials regard the corps as the
first step toward the creation of a "national army." (NATO-KLA-
Kosovo 
</P>
