<HEADLINE> South Africa Bid Chief: England Has No Chance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- England will have no chance of
staging the World Cup 2006 finals, South Africa's bid chief
claimed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to local reports on Friday, Danny Jordaan, who leads
South Africa's bid, fired another salvo in the war of words
between South Africa and England over the bid to host soccer's
showpiece.
</P>
<P>
Quizzed over his dismissive attitude towards England, he said
UEFA's expected support for the German bid made Germany "a
formidable candidate".
</P>
<P>
He claimed South Africa and Germany were the only major
contenders, and that South Africans overwhelmingly support their
country's bid. "Hosting will also make a major contribution to
the economy of South Africa, addressing the very issues, like
poverty and unemployment, which our critics suggest we are
neglecting by pursuing the bid," said Jordaan.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions about South Africa's high crime rate,
Jordaan pointed to 55 major sporting events hosted in South Africa
in recent years, saying 11.4 million people had been involved
without any major incident.
</P>
<P>
"I find it bizarre that South Africa is hosting the 2003 World
Cup in cricket without facing a barrage of crime queries," he said.
"Yet, when it comes to soccer three years later, the fortune-
tellers amongst you seem to think crime will have worsened."
</P>
<P>
However, the All Africa Games have been plagued by a number of
incidents overlooked by Jordaan - including the mugging of a
hockey official, the arrest of a police officer guarding the Games
for car theft, the carjacking of two Games officials and the
firing of gunshots near a bus carrying competitors. 
</P>
