<HEADLINE> O'Neill Vows to Overcome Leicester "Lunacy" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Martin O'Neill is staying as
Leicester manager - but the long-term future of the club is still
up in the air.
</P>
<P>
O'Neill revealed on Friday lunchtime that he will not quit
Filbert Street in the wake of the boardroom power struggle which
has seen chief executive Barrie Pierpoint insist that the manager'
s allies, club chairman John Elsom and plc chief Sir Rodney Walker
resign.
</P>
<P>
The duo are adamant they did not quit at a meeting last Friday
but with four members of the board - Pierpoint and directors Roy
Parker, Gilbert Kinch and Philip Smith - not recognising their
authority, the situation is nothing short of farcical.
</P>
<P>
O'Neill's confirmation of "I am staying" at the club's training
ground brought applause from the 20 or so fans who had gatecrashed
the news conference.
</P>
<P>
They were the same people who had brandished A4 leaflets
proclaiming "Pierpoint out, Parker out" - two of which were placed
on cars belonging to the Leicester manager and Kinch, who met O'
Neill on Friday.
</P>
<P>
At that meeting Kinch asked the former Northern Ireland
international if he knew of a conversation between himself and
Elsom on Wednesday, when the chairman was asked if he would step
down from the board - an option he rejected.
</P>
<P>
And while O'Neill acknowledged the issue must be brought to a
satisfactory conclusion as soon as possible, he also demonstrated
again whose side he is on.
</P>
<P>
He refused to be drawn over whether he would like to work under
Pierpoint, his long-standing adversary, and he said: "I would
prefer it if Mr Elsom stayed as the chairman of the football club
and Sir Rodney Walker continued as chairman of the plc.
</P>
<P>
"I've worked with three chairman in four years and I didn't
envisage working for another one as quickly as this.
</P>
<P>
"They maintain their stance that they haven't resigned, that
they only stormed out of the meeting, and I believe them," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
