<HEADLINE> Reading Welcomes Hoddle's Application </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- English soccer second division
club Reading said Friday that they welcome an application from
Glenn Hoddle for their vacant manager's job, but they will not
approach the former England boss.
</P>
<P>
Club chairman John Madejski, who sacked former boss Tommy Burns
Thursday, insisted there was no rush to find a replacement. "We
will be pleased to hear from Glenn in exactly the same way as we
will be pleased to hear from anybody else interested in the job."
</P>
<P>
He added: "But we are not getting into the business of
approaching anybody. I have learned from the appointment of Tommy
Burns that high profile managers don't always give you everything
they want and sometimes the low profile managers do.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody was absolutely delighted when Tommy joined the club
and he did an awful lot of good. However, in 66 games in charge
he only won 20.
</P>
<P>
"We invested plenty of money in players but I don't believe in
continuing to throw money at things. I can't keep throwing money
down a black hole. I have to get results because this football
club is currently losing 200,000 pounds a month."
</P>
<P>
Madejski said he had telephoned new caretaker manager Alan
Pardew inviting him to take the manager's job on a temporary basis.
Pardew then contacted former England number two John Gorman who
agreed to join as his assistant.
</P>
<P>
"There is no rush to appoint a new manager," added Madejski. "
It's so important to get it right. We have a very good squad of
players and there's no need to rush when we have Alan and John in
charge.
</P>
<P>
"I hope they throw their hats into the ring for the new job. I
would be delighted if they are so successful that we have to keep
them," he added. 
</P>
