<HEADLINE> Humanitarian Aid Reaches East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program
(WFP) on Friday dropped 15 metric tons of rice and blankets at
three locations in East Timor, the United Nations announced
Friday.
</P>
<P>
This was the first humanitarian assistance to reach East Timor
since many local people fled into the mountains due to violence
following the August 30 referendum on independence. More airdrops
are planned for Saturday, WFP said.
</P>
<P>
The International Committee of the Red Cross brought in to the
capital of Dili Friday two plane loads of mostly high-protein
biscuits the same day.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) Sadako Ogata
was on her way to Indonesia Friday to talk with the Indonesian
authorities about how to help the people relocated to West Timor,
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Indonesian military sent to quell
the violence after martial law was imposed ten days ago, began to
pull out of East Timor Friday.
</P>
<P>
There will be about two Indonesian battalions, or 4,000 troops
expected to stay on to secure essential utilities such as water
and electricity for the arrival of the U.N. authorized
multinational force (MNF), Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
So far eight countries have expressed "firm commitments" to the
MNF with negotiations underway for a number of Southeast Asian
countries to take part in the force, Chief of the Australian
Defense Force Admiral Chris Barrie was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council endorsed Wednesday the establishment
of the MNF to restore peace and security in East Timor and U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan hoped that the force would get there
as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
An advance unit is expected to arrive in East Timor on Monday,
according to Australian sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
