<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Rebels to Start Talks with Gov't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's National
Liberation Army (ELN), guerrilla of Colombia, would accept to
start direct peace talks with the government, it was announced
here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
A business leader who attended Thursday's meeting with an ELN
leader in Caracas announced it here.
</P>
<P>
The Caracas meeting, sponsored by Venezuelan President Hugo
Chavez and authorized by the Colombian government, was attended by
business leaders, Colombian Attorney General Jaime Bernal Cuellar
and Pablo Beltran, ELN central committee delegate.
</P>
<P>
One of the business leaders, Sabas Pretelt, said that the talks
can be held even before the release of some 56 hostages captured
during three mass kidnappings registered in the first half of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Another important point is an agreement on a zone of distension
similar to the one granted by the government to the Revolutionary
Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC) to hold peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
FARC is the largest rebel group in Colombia followed by ELN.
</P>
<P>
Contacts between government and the ELN broke off after the
rebel group staged two spectacular mass kidnappings of a
commercial airliner and a church congregation in April and May.
</P>
<P>
Colombia's civil war has cost more than 35,000 lives in the
last decade, as guerrillas, right-wing death squads and the
U.S.-trained army battle for control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990918.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Equity Prices in Greece Soar to New Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Greek equity prices surged to
new records Friday with the general index on the Athens Stock
Exchange (ASE) jumping 0.53 percent to 6,355.04 points, its 53rd
record this year.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE/ASE 20 index also rose 0.65 percent to 3,270.85
points.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 550 billion drachmas (about 1.77 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Advancers led decliners by 180 to 126 with another five issues
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The investment and insurance sectors led the increasing stock
market, ending 5.58 percent and 3.44 percent higher respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
